<HEADLINE> Schroeder Wants Strong EU-Commision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, 11 January (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder called Monday on the European Parliament to ponder key
tasks of financial reform and enlargement before casting ballots.
</P>
<P>
Bonn needed a strong Commission to bring about reform in E.U.
finances by a March summit in order to pave the way for taking in
new member states from Eastern Europe, stressed Schroeder at a
Bonn news conference with embattled European Commission President
Jacques Santer.
</P>
<P>
The European Parliament in Strasbourg was due to open debate
Monday on corruption, fraud and mismanagement charges involving
Santer's Commission, which serves as the 15-nation European
Union's (E.U.) executive branch.
</P>
<P>
Parliament was due to vote Thursday on a motion of
no-confidence over the allegations. A two-thirds majority is
necessary to force the Commission from office and Santer has said
that even if a simple majority in favor of the no-confidence the
Commission will stay on in office.
</P>
<P>
"I plead that we do not only look to the past but that we also
look to the future," said Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
Germany currently holds the E.U.'s rotating presidency.
</P>
<P>
"In order to succeed I need a stable Commission which is
capable of working," he said. "And I am sure the freely elected
parliamentary representatives see this relationship just as I do."
</P>
<P>
But Schroeder declined to make any suggestion to parliament on
how to vote over the corruption charges.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, ex-German Chancellor Helmut Kohl
rejected suggestions from Santer that he consider becoming the
next E.U. Commission president when Santer's term ends next year.
</P>
<P>
"Kohl is not available for this office," said a spokesman for
Kohl. Since losing Germany's election last September, Kohl, 68,
has stayed on in parliament as a regular member of the
conservative opposition.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder repeated earlier warnings that failure to agree on
E.U. finances by March could lead to a delay in taking in new
members from the former East Bloc.
</P>
<P>
"Then and only then enlargement would be delayed," said
Schroeder. The first new E.U. members are not expected to join
before 2003.
</P>
<P>
Germany has demanded a cut in its net annual contribution to
the E.U. of 22 billion marks (13 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
E.U. members must agree on who pays what for the Union for the
period 2000 to 2006 by the end of this year at the latest when
current financial arrangements expire.
</P>
<P>
"There are a few problems here we have to solve," said
Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
Reform of farm subsidies, which devour half the annual E.U.
budget of about 100 billion dollars, remains key to revamping the
Union's finances, he said. Bonn wants member states to start
paying more for their own farmers instead of sending the bill to
Brussels. This is opposed by France.
</P>
<P>
"Every member state must be prepared to compromise," said
Schroeder, who noted that this also included Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
