<HEADLINE> GCC Insists Iraq Comply with U.N. Resolutions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 11 (Xinhua) -- The Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) states have insisted on Iraq's implementation of
all U.N. resolutions related to its invasion of Kuwait in 1990,
Kuwaiti First Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Sabah
Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah said Monday.
</P>
<P>
On the GCC foreign ministers' meeting held in Jeddah, Saudi
Arabia, Sunday, Sabah said the GCC states have taken a joint stand
strongly rejecting threats by the Iraqi regime, particularly those
against Kuwait and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
"The unwavering stand of the GCC showed emphatic rejection of
Iraqi policy of threats and any decision that may be taken to
violate (the United Nations) Security Council resolutions," Sabah
told the Kuwait News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Sabah made the remark after Iraqi officials stepped up a
rhetoric campaign against Kuwait and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Foreign Minister Mahammed Saeed al-Sahhaf said Sunday
night that Kuwait and Saudi Arabia "have directly participated in
the U.S.-British air strikes against Iraq" in mid-December.
</P>
<P>
He said U.S. cruise missiles passed through Kuwaiti airspace
during the bombardment, and dozens of U.S. and British warplanes
flew over Saudi Arabia and Kuwait during the strikes.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Iraqi National Assembly said Sunday that it held
Kuwait and Saudi Arabia responsible for the material and human
losses in the December 16-19 U.S.-British air raids against Iraq.
</P>
</TEXT>
