<HEADLINE> S.Korean Banks Suffer Losses of 9.8 Billion U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 11 (Xinhua) -- South Korean commercial banks
recorded combined net losses of 11.5 trillion won (9.8 billion
U.S. dollars) last year, the highest loss ever in the nation's
history, the Financial Supervisory Service (FSS) said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The commercial banks posting losses are Hanvit Bank, Korea
First Bank, Seoul Bank, Cho Hung Bank, Korea Exchange Bank, Peace
Bank and Housing &AMP; Commercial Bank.
</P>
<P>
Hanvit Bank, a merger of Commercial Bank of Korea and Hanil
Bank, sustained the biggest net loss of 3.35 trillion won (2.8
billion dollars) in 1998, followed by Korea First Bank, which
was sold off to Newbridge Capital of the United States, with a
loss of 2.6 trillion won (2.2 billion dollars), Seoul Bank
reported 2.2 trillion won (1.9 billion dollars) in losses, Cho
Hung Bank lost 1.97 trillion won (1.7 billion dollars), Korea
Exchange Bank lost 840 billion won (700 million dollars), Peace
Bank lost 430 billion won (360 million dollars), and Housing &AMP;
Commercial Bank lost 400 billion won (340 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Key reasons behind the record losses were reportedly bad
loans, the FSS said.
</P>
<P>
However, Hana Bank reported a net surplus of 110 billion won
(90 million dollars), followed by Kookmin Bank's profit of 74.5
billion won (60 million dollars), Shinhan Bank with a surplus of
58 billion won (50 million dollars) and KorAm Bank with 53
billion won (40 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Net losses of provincial-based banks totaled 2.4 trillion won
(2 billion dollars) in 1998. Combined deficits of Seoul-based and
regional banks amounted to 13.9 trillion won (11.7 billion
dollars) in 1998.
</P>
<P>
But, the deficits are less than expected due to the reduced
stock appraisal losses resulting from the recent strong rally in
the Seoul stock market, added the FSS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
