<HEADLINE> U.S. Warplanes Attack Iraqi Air Defense Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 10 (Xinhua) -- Three U.S. warplanes fired
missiles on Monday at an Iraqi air defense site in the northern
no-fly zone after they were targeted, the U.S. Defense Department
said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. planes, two F-15Es strike aircraft and one F-16
fighter, bombed the Iraqi installation after determining they
were about to be attacked by surface-to-air missiles, Defense
Department spokesman Army Col. Richard Bridges said.
</P>
<P>
The planes were on routine patrol in the "no-fly" zone over
northern Iraq when they were illuminated by radar from the Iraqi
surface-to-air missile installation, he said.
</P>
<P>
The planes returned safely to their base in Turkey, Bridges
said, adding that damage to the Iraqi site could not be
immediately determined.
</P>
<P>
The F-15Es fired two AGM-130 air-to-surface missiles and the
F-16 fired one anti-radar missile, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
