<HEADLINE> U.S. Warplanes Fire at Two Iraqi Air Defense Sites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON January 11 (Xinhua) _ Two U.S. Air Force planes
fired missiles on Monday at two Iraqi air defense installations in
northern no-fly zone after determining they were about to be
attacked by surface-to-air missiles, the U.S. Defense Department
said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. planes returned safely to their base in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Damage to the Iraqi site could not be immediately determined,
Defense Department spokesman Army Col. Richard Bridges said.
</P>
<P>
Two U.S. F-15E strike aircraft and one F-16 fighter were on
routine patrol in the ``no-fly'' zone over northern Iraq when they
were illuminated by radar from an Iraqi surface-to-air missile
installation, he said
</P>
<P>
In the first case, two F-15E strike aircraft were on routine
patrol in the northern no-fly zone when they were illuminated by
radar from an Iraqi surface-to-air missile installation, and the
U.S. warplanes fired two AGM-130 air-to-surface missiles in
response. The Iraqis did not fire on the planes, Bridges said.
</P>
<P>
In the other incident, a F-16 fighter fired one-anti-radar
missile after being targeted by Iraqi radar at a separate air
defense installation near Mosul.
</P>
<P>
Bridges described the U.S. attacks as acts of self-defense.
</P>
<P>
"The illumination of an aircraft is certainly a hostile act,"
requiring the U.S. pilots to respond, Bridges said. A pilot whose
plane is illuminated, or ``painted'' by radar, assumes he is about
to be fired upon.
</P>
<P>
The incident happened near the city of Mosul at about 10:45
a.m. Iraqi time (0745 GMT). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
