<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton to Give State of Union Address as Scheduled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 10 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
will give his State of the Union address to Congress and the
nation in mid-January despite calls that he postpone it because
of his impeachment trial, a White House spokesman said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"The president looks forward to delivering the State of the
Union address on January 19th," James Kennedy said, adding that
"we have no intention of being diverted from addressing the
issues that are important to the country."
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who went on trial in the Senate on January 7, stands
accused of two articles of impeachment -- perjury and obstruction
of justice -- in connection with his effort to conceal a sexual
relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky. He
is the second president in U.S. history to be subjected to a
trial, after Andrew Johnson in 1868.
</P>
<P>
With his impeachment trial set to resume on January 14,
Clinton faces the daunting challenge of addressing a joint
session of Congress on January 19 in the midst of Senate proceedi
ngs into whether he should be removed from office on the charges
stemming from his affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
Many Republicans have called for a delay, although Senator
Susan Collins said the timing should be driven by circumstances.
If the Senate was "almost to the conclusion of the trial, the
president should wait. If it looks like it's going to be a longer
period than anticipated, then he should go ahead," she said.
</P>
<P>
Several Democrats also joined the Republicans Sunday in urging
Clinton to either delay the speech or submit it as a written
report instead.
</P>
<P>
However, Senate Democratic Leader Tom Daschle defended
Clinton's decision, saying "the business of the country still
must go on, even if the trial is under way."
</P>
<P>
"It will be uncomfortable clearly, but I don't see any other
real option. Let's get on with the business. This is important,
but so is running the country," Daschle said on CBS's "Face the
Nation."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Constitution requires a president to present Congress
annually with a status report on the nation. The report first was
submitted in writing but, since the days of President Woodrow
Wilson, it has been a formal address. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
