<HEADLINE> VW Record Car Deliveries in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Europe's largest car concern,
Volkswagen, said Tuesday it delivered a record 4.58 million vehicles
in 1998, surpassing by 7.5 per cent the record set the previous year.
</P>
<P>
At VW headquarters in Wolfsburg, the company said its estimated
share of the world market last year came to 11.4 per cent, up from
10.4 per cent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In a breakdown, the company said deliveries of private cars of the
VW brand came to 2.85 million last year, up 8.5 per cent.
</P>
<P>
Audi division deliveries increased 9.8 per cent to 600,000, while
the subsidiary Seat (Spain) showed a 7.2 per cent increase to
432,000, and the Skoda subsidiary (Czech Republic) improved its
deliveries by 8.1 per cent, to 363,000.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, VW commercial vehicle deliveries rose by 4.6 per
cent for a 1998 total of 238,000.
</P>
<P>
By region, VW group deliveries to Western Europe improved by 13.7
per cent to 2.83 million, while those to North America skyrocketed by
53 per cent to 418,900. Even deliveries to the Asia-Pacific region,
despite the economic turbulence, improved by 1.1 per cent to 375,900.
</P>
<P>
But deliveries to South America and South Africa combined plunged
by 22.9 per cent to 588,500 cars, VW said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
