<HEADLINE> Chinese Legislator Says NGOs Are Indispensable Part Of Society </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The new non-governmental
organizations (NGOs) have meant a significant change in China's
social structure and the perfection of the socialist market
economy, according to Zhou Guangzhao, the vice-chairman of the
National People's Congress (NPC) Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
Zhou told the annual meeting of the China Association for
Science and Technology (CAST), of which he is president, here
today that social groups will make up an important part of
China's socialist modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
The registration rules for groups, which were revised by the
State Council, and the provisional regulations on registration
for NGOs mean a great deal for improving the management of NGOs
and safeguarding social stability, Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
Bringing more social groups into NGOs is the principle of
separating politics from social life, Zhou said, and means that
social groups no longer need be affiliated with a certain
government department and can be independent bodies instead.
</P>
<P>
Social groups can be voluntarily formed by people for
activities that help them realize their common goals, he said,
and this will be a guiding principle for societies affiliated
with CAST.
</P>
<P>
Zhou asked all CAST-affiliated societies to take over
functions given up by government offices.
</P>
<P>
CAST has 4.3 million members and is one of the largest NGOs in
China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
