<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nazarbayev Wins New Term as President of Kazakhstan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Kazakhstan President
Nursultan Nazarbayev, 59, was elected as expected to a new
seven-year term, with 81 percent of the votes for him, a
presidential press service official told Xinhua Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The official results gave Communist Party leader Serikbolsyn
Abdildin 14 percent, customs committee head Gani Kasymov four
percent and parliamentary deputy Engels Gabbasov one percent.
</P>
<P>
The presidential election, the first since the former Soviet
republic became independent in December 1991, proceeded in a
peaceful atmosphere. A total of 200 international observers were
deployed to oversee the election.
</P>
<P>
More than 7.13 million voters, or 86.26 percent of the total
eight million electorate, turned out for the election Sunday.
</P>
<P>
According to the April 1995 referendum, Nazarbayev was
scheduled to end his presidency in 2000. However, the Kazakh
parliament revised the constitution in October last year and
decided to hold the election ahead of time.
</P>
<P>
Nazarbayev led Kazakhstan during the Soviet era and became the
republic's president after its independence in 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
