<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Warplane Fires Missile at Iraqi Radar Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. F-16 fighter fired a
HARM missile at a radar site in the northern no-fly zone in Iraq
on Tuesday, the Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. aircraft returned safely to its base in Incirlik,
Turkey. The clash took place at 11 a.m. Iraqi time (0800 GMT),
Pentagon spokesman Col. Richard Bridges said.
</P>
<P>
It wasn't immediately clear why the pilot fired a missile at
the radar site, but Bridges said the "radar posed a threat to
coalition forces."
</P>
<P>
He said there was no further information, but it is possible
the aircraft was being targeted, as has occurred in several
previous incidents over the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
It was the second such military clash this week. On Monday
U.S. fighters attacked two Iraqi air defense missile sites in the
northern no-fly zone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
