<HEADLINE> Russia and France to Further Develop Bilateral Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov and visiting French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine said
here on Tuesday that the two countries will continue to develop
trade and economic partnerships.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also confirmed "the privileged nature of
relations" that exists between the two nations during the
meeting, the Russian premier's spokeswoman Tatyana Aristarkhova
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said that Russia and France have very close positions
on international affairs.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine's visit was very important "for the preparation of
Russian President Boris Yeltsin's visit to Paris late in January
and for an exchange of views on a broad range of issues," said
Primakov.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Primakov and his French counterpart
exchanged views on the current situation in Russia and pressing
international issues.
</P>
<P>
Primakov informed the French foreign minister about efforts
taken by the Russian government to stabilize the domestic
situation.
</P>
<P>
"In this context Primakov stressed the importance of the
Duma's speedy approval of the 1999 budget and an understanding
with the International Monetary Fund (IMF) on the disbursement of
loans agreed upon earlier," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine arrived here on Monday evening for an official visit.
He also met with his Russian counterpart Igor Ivanov earlier on
Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
