<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Bid to Protect Culture Brings Warning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States has warned
Canada that it will strike back at four key industries if Ottawa
proceeds with plans to protect Canadian magazines from
cross-border competition, the Globe and Mail newspaper reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Monday, a top U.S. official gave Canada's ambassador in
Washington, Raymond Chretien, oral notice of U.S. plans to
retaliate by blocking some Canadian steel products, textiles and
apparel, wood products and plastics from access to the U.S.
market.
</P>
<P>
"We're keeping all our options open at this point. That's all
that I can say," Jay Ziegler, a spokesman for U.S. Trade
Representative Charlene Barshefsky, said Monday night.
</P>
<P>
He added that Barshefsky has repeatedly expressed her concerns
about Canada's protectionist cultural policies, and that there
have been a series of meetings between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The costs of the proposed retaliatory measures are estimated
by Canadian officials at between 3 billion Canadian dollars (1.98
billion U.S. dollars and 4 billion Canadian dollars (2.64 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
A Canadian Foreign Affairs official confirmed Monday night
that the private talks had taken place Monday at the Canadian
Embassy, involving deputy U.S. trade representative Richard
Fisher and Canadian Ambassador Chretien.
</P>
<P>
The United States has made no secret of its unhappiness with
Canadian Heritage Minister Sheila Copps' initiatives to protect
two key areas of Canadian culture: magazines and films.
</P>
<P>
In October last year, Minister Copps introduced Bill C-55,
which would make it illegal for Canadian advertisers to place ads
in so-called split-run magazines -- Canadian editions of U.S.
publications which contain little editorial content originating
in Canada.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Copps is preparing legislation to protect
Canadian films. She has met with representatives of the U.S. film
industry, and informed them that she is considering a levy of 3
to 5 percent on all movies and videos distributed in Canada.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
