<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1445 GMT, January 12 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO -- Arab League Secretary General Esmat Abdel-Meguid
expressed surprise Monday at the latest statements made by Iraqi
Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz concerning Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Abdel-Meguid regretted that Aziz made
the statement, which he said would "likely (have) negative impact
on" the upcoming Arab foreign ministers meeting. (Arab
League-Iraq)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States plans to send eight more F-16
warplanes to further enforce the southern no-fly zone in Iraq, a
U.S. defense spokesman said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The eight additional jet fighters, which are specially
adapted to carry sophisticated missiles to destroy anti-aircraft
radars, would also be joined by four more aerial refueling
tankers, said Major Joe LaMarca, a spokesman for U.S. Central
Command in Tampa, Florida. (US-Iraq-Re-enforcement)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will
travel to Saudi Arabia and Egypt later this month for talks on
Iraq and the Middle East peace process, the State Department said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"She will consult with two of our closest allies in the
region on matters of mutual interest. Clearly Iraq and the Middle
East peace process will be on the agenda," spokesman James Rubin
told reporters. (US-Iraq-Albright)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. House of Representatives insisted Monday
that evidence against President Bill Clinton "overwhelmingly
supports" both charges -- perjury and obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
In papers filed with the Senate, the Republican-controlled
House said that "perjury warrants conviction and removal" from
office of a duly elected president under Senate precedents.
(US-House-Clinton)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KAMPALA -- The U.S. Embassy and the British High Commission
in Uganda has been closed following threats by an anonymous
caller that a bomb was to be planted in the premises.
</P>
<P>
An official in the U.S. embassy, who declined to be named,
told Xinhua in a telephone interview Tuesday morning that the
embassy is closed and that he does not know when it will reopen.
(Uganda-Embassies-Close) 
</P>
