<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maier Wins Giant Slalom in Alpine Skiing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Olympic champion Hermann Maier
of Austria won a World Cup giant slalom in Adelboden,
Switzerland, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Compatriot Benjamin Raich, 20, led Maier by 0.16 seconds after
the first leg but Maier roared back in the second run to win in a
combined time of two minutes 12.66 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Raich was third in 2:13.48, behind Maier's Norwegian overall
World Cup rival Kjetil Andre Aamodt in 2:12.94.
</P>
<P>
It was a sweet revenge for Maier, who had vowed to strike back
after he was forced to make do with third place behind Raich in a
giant slalom in his home town of Flachau on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"This was one of the most difficult races of my life," said
Maier, the overall World Cup champion and current leader of the
standings, who had complained of back pains before the race.
</P>
<P>
It was the Austrian's sixth win of the season. He has now won
at Adelboden two years in a row. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
