<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Handles Over 100,000 Corruption Cases In 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese procuratorates handled
108,828 cases of bribery and dereliction of duty in 1998 and
investigated 40,162 persons.
</P>
<P>
Han Zhubin, procurator-general of the Supreme People's
Procuratorate, told a national procurators' conference here today
that last year's crackdown concentrated more on some spectacular
cases.
</P>
<P>
He said the procuratorates investigated 9,389 cases, each of
which involved bribes of more than 50,000 yuan (about 6,000 U.S.
dollars) and the embezzlement of public funds worth more than
100,000 yuan last year.
</P>
<P>
They involved some 1,820 officials above the county level and
7,065 staff members in judicial and administrative offices, he
said. The case of former Beijing Mayor Chen Xitong demonstrated
the determination of the Party and the government in the
anti-corruption campaign.
</P>
<P>
Han also praised the way the cases were handled and said that
procuratorates had joined the anti-smuggling movement as well,
handling 8,469 cases of smuggling and foreign currency-related
crimes, involving 14,554 persons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
