<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Keen on Better Ties With Iran: Ramadan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Iraq is keen on promoting
relations with Iran, which is in the interests of the two
neighboring Muslim peoples, said Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassin
Ramadan on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Ramadan made the remark when receiving Mohammed Sader, an
Iranian foreign undersecretary and personal envoy of President
Mohammad Khatami to Iraqi President Saddam Hussein. Sader arrived
here Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq highly appreciated the Iranian stances during the recent
U.S.-British aggression," the Iraqi News Agency quoted Ramadan as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Iran condemned the mid-December air strikes by the United
States and Britain on Iraq the first day they were launched, and
called for their immediate end.
</P>
<P>
Ramadan hoped that the contacts between Iraqi and Iranian
officials would continue to ease the difficulties facing the joint
committees recently established to discuss pending issues between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
An invitation was extended to his Iranian counterpart for a
visit to Iraq, Ramadan said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq and Iran, which fought an eight-year war in the 1980s,
have been making efforts since last year to solve lingering issues
like the prisoners of war that are in the way of normalizing
bilateral ties. 
</P>
