<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Intensifying Crackdown On Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Han Zhubin, procurator-general
of China's Supreme People's Procuratorate, told a national
procurators' conference here today that the nationwide
anti-corruption crackdown will become more intense in 1999 to
help maintain social stability and economic order in China.
</P>
<P>
Han said that the movement, which started at the beginning of
last year, has halted illicit behavior among law-enforcement
personnel who were abusing power and taking bribes.
</P>
<P>
China's procuratorates investigated 1,557 people working in
law-enforcement and imposed penalties on 1,215 people, 113 of
whom were remanded over to judicial departments for further
investigations of their alleged crimes.
</P>
<P>
Han said procuratorates dismissed 827 procurators from their
positions for being unqualified and had a close look at 20,830
local procurators and anti-corruption directors at the county and
prefectural levels.
</P>
<P>
He said that public security and state security departments
handled 447,472 cases, which involved 689,025 persons, in 1998
and took 380,442 cases, involving 557,925 persons, to court.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the procuratorates had made progress in
handling lawsuits, especially in dealing with holding people in
custody for illegal lengths of time, and had worked at preventing
dereliction of duty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
