<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Large Poisoning Case In Eastern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The victims of a mass
poisoning case in East China's Jiangxi Province have suffered
relapses in the past two days and medical personnel are making an
appeal for outside assistance in treating the illness.
</P>
<P>
By this morning, 35 people had been re-hospitalized after
complaining of headaches, dizziness, or memory loss. Some also
had nervous tics, according to local sources.
</P>
<P>
The first report of the case came on December 25 after some
people of Longnan and Dingnan counties had used some lard
produced by companies in the southern city of Shenzhen. Two
people died and 221 others had to be treated in local hospitals.
</P>
<P>
An investigation showed that the lard contained as much as 29
times the permissible level of tin, causing damage to the nervous
and circulatory systems.
</P>
<P>
A lack of proper medicine was the main reason for the
relapse, explained Lin Weihua, the head of the Longnan Hospital.
Medical departments have sent officials, persaonnel, and 80
vehicles to the area to help out with emergency cases and the
Public Security bureaus of Jiangxi and Guangdong provinces are
searching for the persons responsible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
