<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Information about Namibian Involvement in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Namibian Defense
Ministry has lifted the media blackout on the country's
involvement in the war in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC),
"The Namibian" newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The decision to lift the embargo was taken after discussions
between Defense Minister Erikki Nghimtina and Editor of "The
Namibian" Gwen Lister Monday, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The Namibian government imposed the ban after claiming that
information sent to the media on Namibian casualties in Congo (K)
and other related incidents was distorted.
</P>
<P>
The ban was supported by Namibian Prime Minister Hage Geingob
who said last week that the blackout had been enforced for the
sake of the security of the Namibian forces in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Namibia, together with Zimbabwe, Angola and Chad, sent troops
to the vast central African country when rebels launched a war to
overthrow DRC President Laurent Kabila and his government five
months ago.
</P>
<P>
Nghimtina agreed to lift the ban at Monday's meeting after
expressing his concern about the publication of rumors which could
adversely affect the safety and security of the Namibian soldiers
in the DRC civil war, which began in last August.
</P>
<P>
However, Lister stressed the need for the Namibians to be kept
accurately informed about the situation in the DRC and for more
open channels of communication to be established between the media
and the Ministry of Defense in the public interest, to avoid rumor
and speculation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
