<HEADLINE> Sino-US Trade Volume Grows 12.1 Percent in 1998 (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The total trade volume between
China and the United States grew 12.1 percent in 1998 to have
reached 54.94 billion US dollars, latest statistics show.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the Chinese Customs on Tuesday show that
while China exported 37.98 billion US dollars of commodities to
the United States, up 16.1 percent, it imported 16.96 billion US
dollars worth of goods from the United States, up 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The trade surplus was recorded at 21.02 billion US dollars for
1998, according to the figures.
</P>
<P>
China's main imports from the United States were wheat, corn,
fertilizer, aircraft, chemical products and medical instruments.
Its main exports to the United States include textile products,
garments and footwear, boxes and cases, mechanical and electronic
appliances.
</P>
<P>
The United States remains to be China's second largest trade
partner after Japan while China is the 4th largest trade partner
of the United States.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile U.S. investment in China keeps pouring in last year.
The newly-approved U.S.-invested projects between January and
November last year numbered 1,999. They involved 5.71 billion US
dollars in contractual volume, of which 3.55 billion US dollars
was used. Both volumes increased compared with the same period a
year before.
</P>
<P>
Most U.S. investment covered the mechanical, metallurgical,
oil, electronics, telecommunications, chemical, textile,
foodstuff and light industries, as well as real restate,
finance, insurance, foreign trade, accounting, and cargo shipment
attorney.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation (MOFTEC) said that many U.S.-invested companies had
reported profits and added more investment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
