<HEADLINE> Amateur Team Enjoys Sweet Time in Winter Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, Jilin Province, January 12 (Xinhua) - A week off
work gives the amateur players sweet memories in their ice hockey
life, although they return to Hong Kong, China, without any medal
from the National Winter Games on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The part-time China Hong Kong ice hockey team, led by a
chairman of a constructing company, lost 5-8 to Mudanjiang
Tuesday, its sixth and last loss in the Games, which opened
Sunday with the ice hockey tournament began on January 5.
</P>
<P>
But the losers were happy as the whole squad stayed on the ice
after Thuesday's defeat, cheering, chatting with journalists and
taking photos everywhere.
</P>
<P>
Love and passions of the sport generated much more pleasure
than they expected in the one-week staying in the northeast city
of China, as well as some concerns for the future of China's ice
hockey.
</P>
<P>
"Ice hockey in our country is shrinking after winning the
first two Asian Winter Games in 1982 and 1986. We should put
more efforts to promote the sport," said team leader Li
Guangjing, whose name has run several headliners in sports pages
on local newspapers since he came here on January 4.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that China will revive its conquering position in Asia
as it was in the 80s'."
</P>
<P>
There are only seven teams, besides Hong Kong, in the ice
hockey competition here, with one of them, Jilin, is set to
announce its disbandment after the Games.
</P>
<P>
No players from provinces outside Heilongjiang and Jilin
attended the competition, except the Hong Kong squad.
</P>
<P>
"Even in Hong Kong, people can play ice hockey, why not in
Guangdong or in Fujian provinces?" Li added.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong players, who play ice hockey once a month, train
by themselves and afford their own fortune for the use of ice
rinks in a commercial stadium in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Team member Liu Jiazhu, 26, an auditor in Hong Kong, said, "I
just enjoy playing ice hockey. There's lots of fun."
</P>
<P>
Liu's teammates include driver, businessman, jewellery sailor
and company owner, with most of whom over 30s. 
</P>
