<HEADLINE> Pakistan PM Vows Not to Compromise on Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif Tuesday said there could be no compromise on his
government's drive to eliminate terrorism both from Karachi or in
any part of the country.
</P>
<P>
"There can be no compromise on the government's efforts to
stamp out terrorism, wherever it is, whether in Karachi or in any
other part of the country," Sharif told reporters at Chaklala
Airbase here before departure for Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
He said his government began "a peace mission" in Karachi to
purge the city of terrorism. Theses steps were taken in the port
city in the supreme national interest, he added.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that he would get cooperation from every
section of the society in his efforts to eliminate terrorism from
the country, adding that such cooperation will help further
strengthen the government's endeavors against the scourge of
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"When there will be no terrorism, there will be investment and
the country would move ahead on its path to progress and
prosperity," he said.
</P>
<P>
Elimination of terrorism, he said, was not his dream alone but
the dream of very Pakistani as well.
</P>
<P>
In response to a question about military courts, he said, these
courts "have performed well, and were doing their job, in aid of
the civil power."
</P>
<P>
Whenever there is a need, the government can seek help of the
armed Forces, he added.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the Pakistani government has, as part
of its fresh efforts to combat wanton terrorist activities in the
country, begun to provide elaborate security cover to persons
considered likely targets of terrorist activities.
</P>
<P>
A large number of diplomats, politicians, judges, religious
leaders
and government functionaries have been provided armed and trained
gunmen
for their security, reported the Associated Press of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
This has been reinforced by static guard deployment, sources at
the
Interior Ministry said. While necessary, police escorts have been
provided to minimize chances of terrorist attack.
</P>
<P>
As a preventive measure, a number of outer checkposts have also
been
established in case of emergency or incidents of robbery, dacoity
or car theft. 
</P>
</TEXT>
