<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Remains Largest Steel Producer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- With an output of 114 million
tons in 1998, China remains the world's largest steel producer,
said the United Nations Economic Commission for Europe (UN/ECE)
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
China's crude steel output this past year increased by 5.7
percent, compared with 107.9 million tons in 1997, influenced by
an estimated 7.8 percent growth in GDP, according to the
organization's latest estimates.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, world crude steel production fell 2.5 percent from
798.5 million tons in 1997 to 778.2 million tons in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Although production remained high in the first half of 1998,
the UN/ECE said Russia's currency crisis, economic turmoil in
Latin America, and a retarding effect of the Asian financial
crises depressed output in the latter half of the year.
</P>
<P>
In Latin America, aggregate output registered a 1.5 percent
decrease as a result of the economic crises in this region.
</P>
<P>
However, the situation in Asia was worse. A drastic decrease
in output took place in Japan, South Korea and ASEAN member
countries. Japan's output of 93.55 million tons was the lowest
since 1972. With 39.2 million tons in 1998, South Korea
experienced a decline for the first time in 32 years.
</P>
<P>
In the United States, output decreased for the first time
since 1991. This decrease however was reportedly slight dropping
by 1.0 percent from 98.5 million tons in 1997 to 97.5 million
tons in 1998.
</P>
<P>
In the European Union, crude steel production in 1998
registered an increase of 1.1 percent, which was sustained by
favorable steel demand from the steel-consuming sectors.
</P>
<P>
Russia's currency crisis resulted in a sharp drop of 10.1
percent in crude steel production, slipping from 48.5 million
tons in 1997 to 43.6 million tons in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
