<HEADLINE> Secretariat Employees Go On En Masse Leave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Work in the Central
Secretariat and allied offices in New Delhi, capital of India, was
paralysed Tuesday with employees going on en masse leave,
demanding higher pay.
</P>
<P>
Employees including those in the armed forces headquarters,
Railway Board and External Affairs Ministry went on strike in
response to the call of the Federation of Central Secretariat and
allied offices, Press Trust of India (PTI) said.
</P>
<P>
The strikers demonstrated in front of Railway Bhavan (building)
and other offices, shouting slogans and demanding more pay and
other allowances.
</P>
<P>
According to another report reaching here, operations at banks
in the capital came to a standstill as thousands of bank employees
stopped work for one day, protesting the rejection of their demand
for a 20 percent hike in pay package.
</P>
<P>
The United Forum of Bank Unions said that no bank transaction
could take place in 1,000 branches across the city as 55,000 bank
employees, including 15,000 officers, went on strike. The forum
threatened to launch an indefinite strike unless a settlement was
reached by then. 
</P>
