<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Six Major Reforms In Prosecution System (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- China will have six major
reforms in its prosecution system this year to ensure justice and
the independent rights of prosecutors, Han Zhubin, the Supreme
People's Procuratorate's procurator-general, told a conference of
top prosecutors of provinces, autonomous regions and
municipalities today.
</P>
<P>
The six reforms are: putting prosecution work under greater
public supervision; making the chief prosecutor responsible for a
certain case; instituting an expert consultation mechanism;
improving the work of procuratorate prosecution committees;
streamlining internal structures; and restructuring the personnel
system.
</P>
<P>
Han said that, in putting prosecutors' work under the public
supervision, prosecution offices nationwide shall make their work
procedures more open and publicize developments of major
corruption cases.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors will have to expose every step of their work, from
collecting crime reports, accepting appeals, and courtroom
performance to public inquiries and questions from parties
involved, Han said.
</P>
<P>
Defendants and criminal suspects should be informed of their
rights as well, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
