<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- A robust resources sector
failed to drive the Australian sharemarket higher Tuesday because
of falls in key industrial stocks and concerns over the next
direction for interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index finished 3.1 points weaker
at 2846.3, off an intra-day low of 2830.1.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index rallied 36.0 points or 3.7 percent to
1011.0 following another strong performance from commodity prices
overnight.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, the all industrials came off 39.7 points for a
close of 5096.2.
</P>
<P>
Diversified Australian miner BHP lead the resources sector,
jumping 63.5 cents to 12.785 Australian dollars, while global
miner Rio Tinto firmed 52.1 to 19.591 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index also enjoyed the spotlight, rising 14.3 points to
1146.3 as the price of gold bullion in Sydney closed at 292.05
U.S. dollars per fine ounce, 1.00 U.S. dollar higher than Monday's
close.
</P>
<P>
The banking index lost 32 points to 6523.3 with Westpac bank
the only major to remain positive, up 0.5 of a cent for a finish
of 11.00 Australian dollars. National Australia Bank dipped 8.4
cents to 25.836 Australian dollars, Commonwealth Bank of Australia
dropped 25.6 cents to 22.70 Australian dollars, and ANZ bank shed
11 cents to 10.64 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover reached 400.69 million shares valued at
783.73 million U.S. dollars. Falls pipped rises by 648 against 617
and 382 stocks were steady. 
</P>
