<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Direct Sales Firms Get License for Salesmen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Dozens of sales
representatives working for well-known foreign direct sales
companies in China, who have shifted their business from direct
sales to retailing, have been granted licenses following a period
of training.
</P>
<P>
Foreign direct sales giants like Amway (China), Guangzhou Avon
Co. Ltd. and the Mary Kay Cosmetics (China) Company have received
their licenses from organizations authorized by the State
Administration of Internal Trade (SAIT).
</P>
<P>
China's State Council issued a ban on direct sales in April
last year. Companies engaged in direct sales had to wind up their
business or apply to change their license to that of a regular
retailer by October 31 last year.
</P>
<P>
Following the ban, a total of 64 foreign direct sales
businesses changed their working patterns: one method involves
retailing goods without hiring salesmen while others use sales
assisted retailing. The latter is required to apply for a sales
person license.
</P>
<P>
SAIT ruled in an earlier notice that a licensed sales agent of
a foreign direct sales company must be at least 18 years old,
have signed a service contract of at least one year, and should
have received training or relevant experience of at least two
years.
</P>
<P>
The notice also requires that a licensed sales agent must not
engage in direct sales. When their service contract expires, the
license will be revoked.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 12:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sharjah to Organize Cultural Festival in Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The government of Sharjah, is
to organize a cultural festival in Cairo from January 27 to
February 3 under the title of "Sharjah Cultural Days in Cairo",
the Khaleej Times daily reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The festival will highlight Sharjah's rich cultural history and
creativity through a cultural exhibition, two music and poetry
evenings to be performed jointly by artists from the United Arab
Emirates (UAE) and Egypt and a cultural seminar, according to
Shaikh Issam, Chairman of the Sharjah Department of Culture and
Information (SDCI).
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to present our cultural experience to the world
starting with Arab countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition would display samples of Sharjah's archeology,
heritage, traditional crafts, fine arts and children paintings.
</P>
<P>
The seminar would discuss cultural ties and reciprocal
influences between Egypt and Sharjah.
</P>
<P>
Shaikh Issam, who heads a 14-member delegation to the festival,
said Sharjah and Cairo had strong cultural ties and pointed to
various joint cultural projects they had established particularly
the Sharjah center for Creativity based in Cairo, and the Islamic
Encyclopedia.
</P>
<P>
"We must admit that Cairo is the core of the cultural movement
in the Arab world," he said.
</P>
<P>
The festival is being organized under the instruction of Ruler
of Sharjah Dr. Shaikh Sultan Bin Mohammed Al Qasimi and in
cooperation with the General Book Authority in Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
