<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's New Defense Forces Chief Pledges Transparency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's new Defense
Forces Chief Gen. Mohd Zahidi Zainuddin Tuesday pledged to nurture
a culture of openness and transparency in the military.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Malaysian national news agency
Bernama, Zahidi said he would also concentrate on consolidating
the Malaysian defense forces as an institution of high integrity.
</P>
<P>
Zahidi, who succeeded Gen. Ismail Omar at the end of last
month, said: "My vision is to make the defense forces an open
organization with integrity which the nation can rely upon to
defend the country," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Zahidi said he would take criticisms and be open to views from
all quarters, including the lower ranks.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the importance of human resource development in the
military, saying it was this aspect that eventually mattered as
the officers and men were the ones who would determine the success
or cause the failure of any effort by the military.
</P>
<P>
"As such I believe that human resources are the defense forces'
most vital asset. I consistently believe that without soldiers,
there will be no generals or commanders," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zahidi said the Malaysian defense forces would move towards
maximizing the strength and expertise of each individual member.
</P>
<P>
Zahidi said he was sensitive to understanding in depth the
requirements of the air force and navy in order to attain
tri-service cohesion in taking on the military challenges of the
new millennium.
</P>
<P>
Zahidi, who was promoted from Army Chief, said given that each
service of the defense forces had its own peculiar military
culture, there were organizational loopholes that would have to be
plugged in order to attain desired cohesion.
</P>
<P>
He also pledged to give priority to equipping officers and men
of the forces with knowledge in information technology as part of
efforts to enhance the forces' level of preparedness.
</P>
<P>
Zahidi said any procurement of new weaponry for the military
would be in the context of the modernization of the defense forces
and in national strategic interests and not to join the arms race.
</P>
<P>
He said that Malaysia's defense ties especially with countries
in the region would continue since it had been proven that they
had brought about much benefits in the ASEAN context in
particular.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia harbors no intention of having confrontation
with any country. "Whatever that we do is always in the context of
peace and of preserving our sovereignty and national assets," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
