<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Urged to Promote Implementation of Wye Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian chief negotiator Saeb
Erekat Tuesday called on the U.S. to help boost the Wye River
peace agreement between the Palestinians and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Erekat's words came at a time when U.S. Middle East peace envoy
Dennis Ross is in the region on a mediation tour.
</P>
<P>
Ross should fulfill only one aim on his current trip, namely to
reach a mechanism to enforce the clauses of the accord, Erekat
said in an interview with Egypt's Voice of Arab radio.
</P>
<P>
Ross arrived in Israel Monday for talks with Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
on ways of advancing the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Under the Wye agreeement Arafat and Netanyahu signed last
October in Washington, Israel should withdraw its troops from
another 13 percent of the West Bank in three phases.
</P>
<P>
But the accord was suspended by Israel only after the first
phase was carried out in early December as Israel accused the
Palestinian leadership of igniting violence against it.
</P>
<P>
Israel has threatened to shelve the accord unless the
Palestinians meet conditions including collecting illegal weapons,
reducing police forces, which the Palestinians denounced as
requirements not stipulated in the Wye accord.
</P>
<P>
The implementation of the accord should be completed by the end
of this month, but the Israeli government froze the process under
the pretext of holding early general elections on May 17, Erekat said.
</P>
<P>
There is nothing, at this point, to negotiate, because all the
talks were done at the Wye Plantation in the U.S. last October,
Erekat stressed.
</P>
<P>
"The sole Palestinian demand at this time is specific and
clear-cut, namely the need to implement the Wye River Memorandum,"
the Palestinian official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
