<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Concerned over Transfer of TMD to Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- China considers the
incorporation of Taiwan into the Theater Missile Defense system
(TMD) a violation of the basic principles of international law
and three Sino-U.S. joint communiques, said foreign ministry
spokesman Sun Yuxi here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Sun made the remark at his regular press briefing, labeling
the move a barrier to the improvement and growth of Sino-U.S.
relations and one that will jeopardize the security and stability
of the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the U.S. government will proceed from the overall
development of Sino-U.S. ties and observe the principles outlined
in the three communiques, and its commitments on the issue of
Taiwan," he said, adding that the U.S. should not transfer the
TMD and relevant technology or other advanced weapons to Taiwan,
in order to avoid damaging Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
According to Sun, China also takes note of Japanese
government's decision to launch military surveillance satellites
by year 2002 and join the development of the TMD system.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese side is concerned over the possible military and
political impact of the moves taken by these two countries on
regional and global security," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We consider that peace and development are the mainstream of
our time after the end of the Cold War, and under these
circumstances the deployment and spread of strategic-weapons
systems may trigger a new round of the arms race, thus affecting
world balance and stability," Sun noted.
</P>
<P>
"We hope Japan will observe its constrained defense policy and
adhere to the course of peaceful development," Sun said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
