<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diving World Cup Starts in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The 11th diving World Cup
started Tuesday in Wellington, the capital of New Zealand, with
the Chinese divers winning the two gold medals at stake in the
woman's one-meter and men's 10-meter synchronized events.
</P>
<P>
Governor General of New Zealand Sir Michael Hardie Boys
attended the opening ceremory and declared the 11th diving World
Cup open.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time the World Cup has been held in the
southern hemisphere. More than 100 divers from 24 countries and
regions are competing in 13 team and individual events at the
Wellington Regional Aquatic Center.
</P>
<P>
China, Russia and the United States, the three leading powers
in the diving world, are represented by strong teams of at least
13 divers each. All athletes have an added incentive to perform
well as this competition is the first Olympic diving qualifying
event for the Sydney 2000 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Today's opening ceremony was followed by the woman's one-meter
diving and men's 10-meter synchronized finals.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-six divers from 18 countries and regions took part in
the woman's one-meter competition with six entering the finals
after the preliminaries this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
In the intense finals with five dives for each diver, Irina
Liashko of Russia, who led the preliminaries, kept her top spot
after three dives until the fourth attempt which dropped her to
fourth place.
</P>
<P>
The 16-year-old Chinese teenager Zhang Jing, who ranked fourth
in the preliminaries, eventually succeeded in defending her title
with 278.58 points.
</P>
<P>
Chantelle Michell of Australia gained 274.86 points for the
silver medal, with the bronze medal went to Chinese Yang lan on
263.10 points.
</P>
<P>
Seven pairs contended for the top honour in the men's 10-meter
synchronized diving where China's famous divers Sun Shuwei and
Tian Liang had the best performances for 341.25 points, beating
the six other pairs with ease.
</P>
<P>
Australian Tony Lawson and Mathew Helm, Mexican Eduardo Rueda
and Fernando Platas won the silver and bronze medals respectively
with less than 300 points.
</P>
<P>
The World Cup competition continues till Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
