<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 19 Killed in Southwest China Traffic Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, January 12 (Xinhua) -- A mini-bus with 20 people
aboard rolled down a 70-meter-high slope in southwest China's
Guizhou Province at about 4:30 pm on January 6, leaving 19 dead
and one seriously injured, local authorities announced here
today.
</P>
<P>
The bus, which belonged to the No.3 Bus Company of Guizhou
Province, was on its way back to Guiyang, capital of Guizhou,
from Qianxi County in the western part of the province when it
apparently went out of control around a sharp curve and plunged
to the bottom of the hill.
</P>
<P>
Eighteen people were killed instantly, and the two seriously
injured passengers were pulled from the wreckage and rushed to a
nearby hospital, but one died on the way.
</P>
<P>
Hospital authorities said the one survivor arrived in coma but
has since regained consciousness and is now completely out of
danger, adding that he will be sent back to Guiyang tomorrow
morning for further treatment.
</P>
<P>
Traffic police in Qianxi and bus company managers said the
cause of the accident was still under investigation, but they
suspect that the poor road conditions may be to blame.
</P>
<P>
"This part of the road had been the site of many previous
accidents," one traffic policeman noted.
</P>
<P>
Guizhou is one of China's most renowned mountainous provinces,
and as a local saying puts it, "One can hardly find three square
feet of level ground here." 
</P>
</TEXT>
