<HEADLINE> Education in Mozambique Undertakes Rapid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Minister of Education
Arnaldo Nhavoto has hailed the development of education in his
country saying the number of schools and enrollment has been the
highest since the country gained its independence in 1975.
</P>
<P>
Most of the education networks which were destroyed during the
civil war have been recovered, Tuesday's Noticias newspaper quoted
him as saying.
</P>
<P>
The government has attached great attention to education after
1992 when peace was attained, said the minister, adding that
primary schools has increased from over 5,000 in 1997 to 6,114 in
1998, and will reach 6,600 by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the enrollment in primary schools
will hit 2. 3 million at the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The number of high schools will grow from 86 at present to 94
by the end of 1999 with the enrollment growing from 60,352 to
71,512 at the end of the year. 
</P>
