<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Seconds, Everything Done </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, Jilin Province, January 12 (Xinhua) -- When Olympic
silver medallist Xu Nannan led Changchun to win the women's
freestyle skiing, the first gold medal in China's Ninth Winter
Games, her name appeared on the official web site just three
seconds after the results were confirmed by chief referees.
</P>
<P>
The official national winter games' site --
http://sport.jl.cninfo.net, receives about 1,600-1,700 hits daily
since it opened on the New Year Day.
</P>
<P>
Though it was not the first time for engineer Han Jian,
director of the hub, to install a network for sports tournament,
it's the only one he can boast of.
</P>
<P>
"We grant instantness for every one who'd like to know the
national winter games on web," said Han, also chief of the
computer technology electronic information center of the State
Sports Commission.
</P>
<P>
"Quickness was always in my mind when I built the network.
However, I didn't realize it in the Eighth National Games in
Shanghai in 1997."
</P>
<P>
The Atlanta Olympic Games in 1996 was the first sports games
to be exploited by the Internet, but it was until the Nagano
Winter Olympics last February that people started to enjoy
watching the Games on website worldwide.
</P>
<P>
"Competition results can be transferred to the host computer
in the center instantly after the games, and to the web
simultaneously. It takes just three seconds in the process," Han
said.
</P>
<P>
"A data-transferring cable connects the results screen in the
stadium and the mainframe in the center, and everything is done
by the computer during a span of a blink.
</P>
<P>
"In the Shanghai National Games, a group of 20 typists were
hired to put the results into the Internet, which wasted half an
hour before it got hits."
</P>
<P>
A team of 20 computer experts worked for four months to
install the information network for the winter games, which cost
just one million RMB (120,000 U.S. dollars), comparing to 82.8
million RMB (10 million U.S. dollars) expense and a team of 200
Spanish experts at the Bangkok Asian Games last December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
