<BODY>
<HEADLINE> mee011210hke - Jordanian House Approves 1999 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Jordanian House of Deputies
(lower house of parliament) has approved the 1999 fiscal budget
with a projected seven percent deficit, Radio Jordan reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Of the 67 deputies who attended the session Monday, 55 voted in
favor of the draft budget law, which is to be referred to the
Senate for further debate and endorsement.
</P>
<P>
The budget of 2.16 billion Jordanian dinars (3.24 billion
U.S. dollars), presented to the House by Finance Minister Mishail
Marto last December, put the current expenditure at 1.68 billion
dinars (2.37 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The capital expenditure in the budget is 477 million dinars
(667.8 millions dollars), which analysts believe too low for a
robust economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
The seven percent budget deficit is in line with the target
imposed by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) for renewing its
financial aid to the reform program of the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and the IMF are expected to sign an agreement later this
month on a new three-year reform program following the kingdom's
failure to achieve sustainable economic growth in the past three
years.
</P>
<P>
The government holds out the hope that the 1999 budget will
help spur the sluggish growth, which was caused by instabilities
over Iraq, Israel, plunging oil prices in the Gulf and a decline
in overseas remittances.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the government fears measures to control
deficits will further push the economy into recession.
</P>
<P>
Critics of the budget have also echoed the concerns. They
believe the government is unable to solve its twin dilemma of
rising unemployment and poverty while keeping a lid on public
expenditure, and keeping the deficit below seven percent.
</P>
<P>
With the seven percent deficit ceiling, the government can
hardly achieve a growth rate higher than three percent in 1999,
economists said.
</P>
<P>
They expressed the belief that Jordan needs at least a six
percent economic growth to cope with the population growth of the
country, which stood at three percent in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Bourse Up 0.61 Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Stock Exchange of Thailand
(SET) index on Tuesday gained 0.61 points from Monday to close at
399.81.
</P>
