<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coffee Exports to Drop in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is expected to export
35,000 tons of coffee in 1999, a sharp drop of 65.7 percent from
58,000 tons in 1998, Thai News Agency (TNA) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
TNA quoted a source from the industry as saying that the sharp
drop is attributed to unexpectedly lower coffee supplies.
</P>
<P>
The Agriculture Minister projected that the country's coffee
output for the 1998/1999 crop season (October-September) would
reach 59,883 tons compared with 78,548 tons in the previous crop
year.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's coffee exports are mostly of the Robusta variety. It
is normally traded at 100-150 U.S. dollars per ton discount to
London prices.
</P>
<P>
The country's coffee was severely hurt by the El Nino weather
phenomenon in late 1997, which has devastated many trees and was
one of the key reasons for the expected fall in output and export,
the source said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the coffee production is likely to be reduced
significantly by the government's plan to encourage growers to
switch to more lucrative crops such as oil palm and corn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
