<HEADLINE> Manila Says Peace Talks Should Be Held in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Tuesday that it has no intention of holding formal peace talks
with the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) in Malaysia or
anywhere outside the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
"The government is not entertaining any intention of holding
formal peace talks with the MILF outside the country," said
Presidential Spokesman Jerry Barican in a statement released here.
</P>
<P>
He was denying reports that the Philippines has asked Malaysia
to host the formal peace talks with the MILF scheduled for the
first week of February.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will continue peace negotiations with
the Muslim rebel group within the framework of the constitution.
</P>
<P>
The 12,000-strong MILF, the major rebel group based in
Mindanao, the southern Philippines, is fighting for an independent
Islamic state. But the demand has been rejected by the government.
 
</P>
