<HEADLINE> Ugandan Minister Denies Bribing MPs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's embattled Minister of
State for Finance and Economic Development Sam Kuteesa has
categorically denied accusations that he bribed some MPs to
withdraw their signatures from the censure petition against him.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the announcement in a statement Monday,
according to the Monitor newspaper.
</P>
<P>
He said he had never given any money to any MPs or any form of
inducement for the purpose of requesting them to withdraw his or
her signature against him.
</P>
<P>
However, the Monitor newspaper reported on January 8 that MPs
backing the censure had alleged that some of their colleagues
trying to withdraw their signatures from the petition had been
bought by the minister who was reportedly involved in
improprieties in the country's privatization process.
</P>
<P>
The censure motion that seeks to unseat Kuteesa from his
ministerial job, charging him with influence peddling and cheating
Uganda Airlines, will be up for debate when the Parliament returns
for debate.
</P>
<P>
Some previous reports here said President Yoweri Museveni was
protecting the embattled minister because Kuteesa's wife is sister
to First Lady Janet Museveni. 
</P>
</TEXT>
