<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 09:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Seeks Peaceful Solution to Iraqi Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Iran has said that it will use
all diplomatic means to find a peaceful solution to the Iraqi
crisis as Baghdad entered a new confrontation with its neighboring
Kuwait and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi told the English
daily Iran News published on Tuesday that Iranian Deputy Foreign
Minister for African and Arab Affairs Mohammad Sadr is in Iraq for
talks with Iraqi officials.
</P>
<P>
"We are concerned about the Iraqi issue and do not want the
issue to surface again," Asefi said, adding that Sadr will also
visit other regional states to help broker peace and to use all
diplomatic means to bring the Iraqi crisis to an end.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain launched air strikes on Iraq for four
consecutive nights on December 16-19 with a declared aim of
punishing it for not cooperating with the U.N. weapons inspectors,
who are authorized to monitor Iraq's elimination of all weapons of
mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The weapons inspections began in 1991 after the Gulf War, set
off by Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Iraq held Kuwait and Saudi Arabia accountable for
the property and human losses during the air strikes because they
allowed the U.S. and Britain to use their space and bases for the
bombardment.
</P>
<P>
Iraq also denied admitting the current Iraqi-Kuwaiti borders
determined by U.N. resolution 833 in May 1993. It also rejected a
Saudi proposal on easing the U.N. sanctions, which was imposed on
Iraq following its invasion of Kuwait, saying its a trick of Saudi
Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait and Saudi Arabia have reportedly been on alert after
Iraq's war-like rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Iraq's territorial claim on Kuwait, the Iranian
spokesman said that such a move is not a proper way to solve
differences and the region should be governed through negotiations
and tension-free talks.
</P>
<P>
He voiced Tehran's opposition to any possible conflict between
Iraq and Kuwait, saying that "we are of the opinion that the two
sides should not engage themselves in such a conflict because this
could be the worst problem in the region."
</P>
<P>
"Foreign powers, which are waiting for a pretext to protect
their vested interests in the region, will abuse the situation,"
Asefi warned.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Iraqi issue is among the top priorities of
Iran's foreign policy and the Foreign Ministry has formed a
headquarters to follow up the development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commission to Decide on PAL Rehabilitation Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Securities and Exchange
Commission (SEC) of the Philippines may hand out by early February
its verdict on a rehabilitation program intended to put Philippine
Airlines (PAL) back on its feet, Finance Secretary Edgardo
Espiritu said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a radio interview, the secretary said the SEC's decision
should pave the way for PAL to get the cash flow it needs to pay
off its debts, which now amount to 2.1 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Once the SEC approves the program, it will lead to the
sequence of cash flow for PAL through capital infusion and
additional loans, as well as loan restructuring," Espiritu said.
</P>
<P>
The SEC still has a big say on who will form PAL's board of
directors, he said.
</P>
<P>
The secretary said PAL Chairman Lucio Tan will continue to be
on top of the PAL board as majority stockholder and can still
influence board decisions, although he cannot interfere in the
airline's management anymore.
</P>
<P>
"Tan will just set the policies and the management will follow
them," he said.
</P>
<P>
PAL will be under a new management team starting Wednesday,
when four former executives of the Kong Kong-Based Cathay Pacific
Airways take over.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu said the airline needs cash infusion amounting to some
6 billion pesos (150 million dollars) to support its daily
operations and pay long-outstanding accounts.
</P>
<P>
President Joseph Estrada said last week that he wanted to keep
PAL flying at all costs because of its impact on all sectors of
the nation's economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
