<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lianyungang Increases Cargo Capacity in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIANYUNGANG (JIANGSU), January 12 (Xinhua) -- The port city of
Lianyungang in east China's Jiangsu Province, the eastern end of
the New Eurasia Continental Bridge, handled 17.6 million tons of
cargo in 1998, a record high after declines for two successive
years.
</P>
<P>
According to Li Anqing, business section chief of the
Lianyungang Port Office, the cargo handling capacity of the port
increased by 10.2 percent in 1998 compared with 1997, surpassing
the national average increase rate of 1.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The port mainly handles the transport of coal, oil, grain and
chemical fertilizers. Its coal transport volume increased by 1.3
million tons in 1998 over 1997, up 23.6 percent, while that of
chemical fertilizers increased by 200,000 tons, an increase of 81
percent over 1997.
</P>
<P>
Li attributed these achievements to the attention paid by the
port office to expanding the domestic market and better
coordination among railway, highway and shipping departments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
