<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 09:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Promises Extra Aid to Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government has pledged
to seek from Congress 100 million U.S. dollars in additional aid
to Jordan over the next 21 months to help alleviate the kingdom`s
economic pains.
</P>
<P>
Jordan Ambassador to the U.S. Marwan Muasher said the
U.S. government made the pledge during a meeting between Jordanian
King Hussein Ibn Talal and U.S. Presdent Bill Clinton in
Washington last week, the Jordan Times reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The abmassador said Jordan`s economic difficulties were a main
issue during the meeting between the U.S. president and the
Jordanian king.
</P>
<P>
"We expect to receive the first extra 50 million dollars in
October 1999 and the rest in October 2000, " Muasher said.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the U.S. Congress agreed to provide 225 million
dollars to Jordan in 1999, including 150 million dollars in
economic assistance and 75 million dollars in military aid.
</P>
<P>
During a brief visit to Amman on December 15, 1998,
U.S. Secretary of State Madeline Albright also pledged to seek
from the U.S. Congress an extra 200-million-dollar in security
aid to Jordan to bolster the kingdom`s ability to cope with
regional turmoil.
</P>
<P>
The 200 million dollars will be provided to Jordan during
the next three years, approximately 66 million dollars a
year.
</P>
<P>
Muasher said if the U.S. Congress approved the additional
packages, Jordan will receive a total of 341 million dollars from
the United States in 1999, including 200 million dollars in
economic aid and 141 million dollars in military aid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
