<HEADLINE> Shortage of Granaries Damages China's Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, January 12 (Xinhua) -- A shortage of grain silos has
meant that almost a seventh of China's grain output last year has
had to be stored in the open, leaving it open to attack by rats,
to be damaged by fires and soaked by rains.
</P>
<P>
The country grew 490 billion kg of grain last year but many of
its silos are old and good harvests over the past four years have
increased pressure on storage facilities.
</P>
<P>
Now the central government has pledged to invest 18 billion
yuan to build new granaries that can store an additional 27.5
billion kg by the summer of the year, and will also upgrade a
number of older silos.
</P>
<P>
According to Liang Zhiqiang, a 52-year-old farmer in Inner
Mongolia Autonomous Region, one of China's largest grain
producing areas, the crop is being ruined by rats and the weather.
</P>
<P>
The new measures will also help reform the grain distribution
system, improve the country's macro-control on agriculture, and
purchase more grain from the farmers, said Wang Fengqi,
vice-chairman of Inner Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
He added that the central government will build an additional
16 granaries in the region alone.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
