<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Michael Jordan to Retire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Chicago Bulls superstar
Michael Jordan, considered the greatest basketball player of all
time, will announce his retirement this week, according to
today's media reports across the United States.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times, the Associated Press, USA Today and The
Denver Post have all reported that the 35-year-old legend would
announce his decision to call it quits at a news conference on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speculations as to Jordan's future have been rife since NBA
players and bosses reached a last-minute settlement last
Wednesday to end the six-month lockout. Jordan, refusing to make
any public decision regarding his future during the lockout, had
been in the Bahamas on vacation, but returned this week to
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
During his 12-plus seasons in the NBA, Jordan rewrote the
regular and postseason record books, becoming the most
recognisable and highest-paid athlete in the world in the process.
</P>
<P>
He led the league in scoring a record 10 times, was selected
Most Valuable Player of the NBA Finals six times and All-Star
Game MVP three times in 11 appearances.
</P>
<P>
The gravity-defying guard is third all-time in career scoring
with 29,277 points, behind only dominating centers Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar and Wilt Chamberlain, and holds the record for
points per game, averaging 31.5 a game throughout his amazing
career.
</P>
<P>
He left basketball following the 1992-93 championship season
to try his hand at professional baseball before making a comeback
to the Bulls late in the 1994-95 campaign.
</P>
<P>
Jordan turned in even better performances to carry the Bulls
back to more NBA titles and last season he gave one of the most
remarkable show in his glorious career by sinking the winning
shot of the NBA Finals to give Bulls a third consecutive
championship and sixth title in eight years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
