<HEADLINE> CCTV Prime Time News Rebroadcast in Mongolian Language </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HUHHOT, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Nearly six million people of
Mongolian ethnic group across China are now able to watch
Mongolian-dubbed TV news programs the same day as they are
broadcast in standard Chinese.
</P>
<P>
 The Mongolian-dubbed TV news is actually broadcast to 53
countries and regions in Asia-Pacific region through satellite.
</P>
<P>
 This is the first time that Mongolian audiences have been
able to watch "today's news" both in Chinese and their own
language since 1969, when north China's Inner Mongolian
Autonomous Region set up a local TV station.
</P>
<P>
 The dubbed TV news programs last 30 minutes and are
broadcast at 7:00 p.m. in the evening by China Central Television
(CCTV). Each program is quickly translated into Mongolian and
broadcast at 10:30 p.m. by the Inner Mongolian Autonomous
Region's own TV station.
</P>
<P>
 Before now, due to shortage of funds, equipment and
translators, the Inner Mongolian Autonomous Region was not able
to broadcast Mongolian-dubbed news the same day it was broadcast
by CCTV, China's only national TV station.
</P>
<P>
 The TV Station of Inner Mongolia's Autonomous Region
started to broadcast programs in Mongolian on October 2, 1976.
Many audiences from Mongolia, Russia, and Hungary take a keen
interest in them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
