<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Urged to Tackle Financial, Economic Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists were urged
today by Vice Premier Wen Jiabao to use their expertise to help
tackle the country's financial and economic problems.
</P>
<P>
At an annual working conference of the China Association for
Science and Technology (CAST), which opened here today, Wen
presented the scientists with a full analysis of the
international financial crisis and the pressing economic issues
facing China.
</P>
<P>
"You are expected to study the relationship between finance
and the economy and science and technology, and give the
government your advice for tackling important problems related to
the development of the national economy and science and
technology," Wen told the scientists.
</P>
<P>
He said that economic development increasingly depends on
scientific and technological advances, and that some countries
suffered greatly under the impact of Asian financial crisis
because their economic growth lacks scientific and technological
support.
</P>
<P>
An economy without the support of science and technology, and
science and technology divorced from serving economic development
both lack vitality, the vice premier said.
</P>
<P>
With a membership of 4.3 million, CAST is the largest
scientific organization in the world, and Chinese scientists
gather annually to discuss major scientific tasks.
</P>
<P>
Wen called on Chinese scientists to help promote development
of the agricultural economy and the reform of state-owned
enterprises, and to offer more scientific and technological
services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
