<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Withdrawal Plan Meets With Lebanon's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon has expressed
reservation about a four-point plan concerning the Israeli
withdrawal from south Lebanon offered by Japanese Foreign Minister
Masashiko Komura.
</P>
<P>
Komura offered the plan to leaders of six Arab countries during
his tour to the region from January 5 to 13.
</P>
<P>
The four points are the withdrawal of Israeli forces should be
implemented as stipulated by U.N. Security Council Resolution 425,
the withdrawal should lead to a comprehensive Middle East peace,
the parties should discuss concrete steps for a withdrawal without
pre-conditions and the international community should render
support to stabilize south Lebanon after the Israeli pullout.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss said in an interview with
the Daily Star Monday night that his government agreed with the
first point but disagreed with the third step, which calls for
discussing the details of a withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
"We are not prepared for any talks or negotiations nor security
arrangements with Israel," he added.
</P>
<P>
Asked if he believed the proposal would lead to a withdrawal,
Hoss said "In the face of Israel's intransigence, I do not expect
much."
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a self-declared security zone in south
Lebanon in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from
Lebanese guerrillas cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
The resolution 425, which was approved by the U.N. in 1978
following Israeli's first invasion of Lebanon, calls for an
unconditional Israeli withdrawal from the country.
</P>
<P>
Last April, Israeli cabinet endorsed the 20-year-old resolution
but linked the implementation of it with a negotiated security
arrangement with Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and its ally Syria flatly rejected the offer, asking
the Jewish state to withdraw troops without any pre-conditions.
</P>
<P>
A western diplomat in Beirut said that it is difficult for
Tokyo to market the plan despite polite noises from Lebanon, Syria
and Israel.
</P>
<P>
"It comes closer to Israeli thinking," the diplomat said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
