<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4000-Year-Old Skeletons Found in Chengdu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- A construction worker recently
stumbled upon a skeleton in downtown Chengdu, capital of
southwest China's Sichuan Province, and the bones have been dated
as 4,000 years old, the Wenhui Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The worker, Li Shujun, came across a leg bone six meters under
ground at a construction site, which aroused the interest of
local archeologists, the Shanghai-based newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
After two days of careful excavation, scientists unearthed a
complete skeleton with all the bones and teeth intact, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
Alongside the mature skeleton lay another, smaller one, which
was badly decomposed and the experts were unable to determine its
sex or age.
</P>
<P>
After a complete examination of the intact skeleton, archeolog
ists determined it was that of a man who lived in the early part
of the Xia Dynasty (21 century - 16 century B.C.) and was 1.72
meters tall.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
