<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment Flow in Zambia Disappointing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has performed badly in
attracting foreign direct investment due to poor infrastructure,
the Zambia Investment Center (ZIC) has disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia Tuesday quoted the ZIC acting director-general
Margaret Mwanakatwe as saying the country lacked well-established
infrastructure to attract foreign direct investment compared with
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Mwanakatwe was speaking at the high level round-table meeting
on the business environment for foreign direct investment to
Zambia held here in Lusaka on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The state of any host country's infrastructure was a major
consideration when a decision on direct foreign investment was to
be made, she said, adding the road network in Zambia needed a lot
of attention while the airports and harbors needed urgent
rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
The rail links were also in a dire need of rehabilitation and
expansion, she said.
</P>
<P>
Mwanakatwe also noted need for private sector investment in
rehabilitating such infrastructure, saying the government alone
would not be in a position to accomplish the task.
</P>
<P>
She said the government had a major responsibility to ensure
that the environment was conducive to private sector
participation. It also needed to consider how infrastructural
investment into rural areas would be enhanced, which had prompted
the ZIC to focus many sectors in a bid to attract potential
investors.
</P>
<P>
Officially opening the meeting, Danny Pule, deputy minister of
Finance and Economic Development, said the government is deeply
committed to ensuring that Zambian infrastructure is provided with
needed investment to be able to support investment.
</P>
<P>
Pule said having established a firm basis for private sector
confidence in the Zambian economy, the government intends to build
partnership with the private sector at new and more challenging
level.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was organized by the Foreign Investment Advisory
Service (FIAS), a joint service of the International Finance
Corporation and the World Bank, in collaboration with the Swedish
International Development Cooperation Agency (SIDA). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
