<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rabe's Former residence in Nanjing to be Preserved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The city government of
Nanjing, capital of east China's Jiangsu Province, has decided to
preserve forever the former residence of John D.Rabe, author of
"Rabe's Diary."
</P>
<P>
Today's Wenhui Daily reported that the residence will be
preserved as historical evidence of Japanese militarists'
invasion and massacre.
</P>
<P>
Rabe was a representative of the Siemens Company in Nanjing
when war broke out there, and he witnessed the atrocities
committed by the invading Japanese troops in 1937 and recorded
what he saw on a daily basis from September to the following
February.
</P>
<P>
During that period, Japanese troops slaughtered more than
300,000 civilians and unarmed soldiers in a nightmare remembered
as the "Nanjing Massacre."
</P>
<P>
The daily said that Rabe's former residence is located at No.1
Xiaofenqiao in downtown Nanjing. Rabe risked his own life in
helping to save the lives of more than 200,000 victims in the
so-called 'security zone.'
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of this year, a number of historians and
other scholars learned that Rabe's former residence might be torn
down for road expansion, and they urged the city government to
change its plan, and the local government accepted this proposal.
</P>
<P>
In a related development,, preparations began on Monday for a
Chinese film version of Rabe's Diary; the script is expected to
be completed by May and filming is scheduled to begin in
September.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smuggling Rampant in Southern Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Statistics show that smuggling
in Africa, particularly in southern Africa, is on the increase and
continues to haunt the governments with no solution in sight.
</P>
<P>
According to a baseline survey done by Independent Management
Consultancy Service (IMCS) based in Lusaka, various goods worth
millions of U.S. Dollars are traded day and night without being
recorded.
</P>
<P>
Eight Border points including Chirundu bordering Zimbabwe and
Mpulungu along Lake Tanganyika were monitored by IMCS from
September 1997 to August 1998, according to Tuesday's Times of
Zambia.
</P>
<P>
During the period, nearly 15 million Dollars of goods were
smuggled to Zambia through the border points.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural commodities recorded four million Dollars,
processed food, three million Dollars, live animals, about 131,000
Dollars, beverages, four million Dollars, manufactured goods, two
million Dollars, textiles, 1.3 million Dollars while other
commodities had about 317,000 Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Over 29 millions Dollars of goods were smuggled out of the
country during the period, of which 11 million Dollars came from
agricultural products, five million Dollars from processed food,
435,000 from live animals, 853,000 from beverages, 156,999 Dollars
from farm inputs, seven million Dollars from manufactured consumer
goods, four million Dollars from textile and 910,000 Dollars from
other commodities.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) recorded the largest
import of the unrecorded goods from Zambia worth 17.5 million
Dollars, the statistics show.
</P>
<P>
In the same period 4.8 million Dollars of goods were smuggled
to Zambia from DRC.
</P>
<P>
Through Chirundu and Victoria Falls, 3.95 million Dollars of
goods were smuggled from Zimbabwe to Zambia with 1.95 million
Dollars of goods to Zimbabwe from Zambia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fewer Overseas Tourists Visit Chinese Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Some 2.2 million overseas
tourists visited Beijing in 1998, down four percent from 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, the Chinese capital earned 2.35 billion U.S. dollars
from these travelers, an increase of 4.4 percent over 1997,
according to statistics released today by the Beijing Tourism
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Officials attributed the drop in the number of overseas
tourists to the influence of the Asian financial crisis, and said
the number of Asian tourists dropped by 20 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
Beijing, the number-one travel destination in China, has plans
to attract 2.31 million overseas tourists this year and earn 2.5
billion U.S. dollars from tourism.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
