<HEADLINE> Consumer Complaints on the Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Both the quantity and quality
of consumer complaints are increasing in China according the
China Business News, which says this indicates that people are
becoming more aware of their consumer rights.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the China Consumer Association (CCA) handled about
800,000 complaints, as compared with only several thousand dealt
with each year in its early days.
</P>
<P>
While most consumers expect to return faulty goods and have
them replaced or repaired, many now are also demanding apologies
and even compensation.
</P>
<P>
Another interesting change is the drop in the value of the
goods. Last year, more than 50 percent of complaints involved
less expensive consumer goods, the newspaper published by the
State Administration of Internal Trade says.
</P>
<P>
There is also a new trend which sees people complaining about
poor service in the tourism and telecommunications sectors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 150-year-old Kingdom of Heaven's Frescoes Need Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Randomly parked cars and a market now occupy the vacant lot in
front of the former official residence of the leaders of the
so-called Kingdom of Heaven who led the Taiping Revolution in the
19th century in Nanjing, capital of east China's Jiangsu
Province, the Beijing Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
At the ruined site, the wood-and-brick house, now dilapidated,
is unable to withstand fierce winds and heavy rains, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
According to painting experts and archeologists, the 18
frescoes were influential during the Taiping Revolution, the
largest peasant uprisings in China's history.
</P>
<P>
State cultural relics protection authorities rehabilitated the
frescoes and renovated the house in 1991, but they are still in
danger of disappearing, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Because of a lack of sufficient funds, experts suggest that
domestic or overseas individuals finance the work of protecting
this historical site, the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Sculpture Exhibits in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Beijing visitors today have
chance to see a group of 100 Italian-made wooden warriors, which
have different approaches but similar artistic results with the
terra-cotta found in the Qinshihuang tomb in China 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Mario Ceroli made his sculpture titled China in 1966 with log.
The wooden army forces resemble to clay warriors molded during
the Qin Dynasty (221-207 B.C.) in clothes and hair style and
formation.
</P>
<P>
Probably Western artists and the Chinese share something
similar in artistic creation and evaluation, an assistant with
the Capital Museum said.
</P>
<P>
However, the 61-year-old sculptor's work also show
characteristics owned by Western people, such as curly hair of
the warriors.
</P>
<P>
In 1960s and 70s, artistic works with the Chinese theme
thrived in Western countries. Among those artists, Ceroli led a
unique style of "arte povera", or art of the poor.
</P>
<P>
He obtained many awards and carried out exhibition tours
throughout the world. Coinciding with Rome Mayor Francesco
Rutelli's visit to Beijing, the exhibition will last five days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Business Props Up Coastal Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The private sector accounts
for over 50 percent of the retail sales in China's affluent
coastal areas, according to China Business Times.
</P>
<P>
The conclusion is based on a survey carried out in 18 coastal
cities including Dalian, Qinhuangdao, Tianjin, Yantai, Qingdao,
Lianyungang, Nantong, Shanghai, Ningbo, Wenzhou,
Fuzhou,Guangzhou, Zhanjiang, Beihai and the four special
economic zones of Shenzhen, Xiamen, Shantou and Zhuhai.
</P>
<P>
The results emphasize the important role of the private sector
in ending the country's long-standing commodity shortage and in
promoting the reform of the distribution sector and commercial
enterprises, the newspaper quotes market analysts as saying.
</P>
<P>
The survey also shows that the growth of private commerce,
which was very fast a few years ago, has slowed down due to the
country's economic restructuring. While the growth in most of
the coastal cities went as high as 80 percent in 1995, the rate
dropped to somewhat 20 percent in the first half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Despite this, the private sector has still exhibited more
remarkable vigor and self-adjustment in the face of growing
fierce competition in the commercial sector. While many
state-owned department stores and other commercial enterprises
have been plagued by low efficiency, with some being forced to
close down, private businesses have proved to be more efficient
and flexible, the analysts say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
