<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Special Envoy Leaves Angola for Headquarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Sevan Benom, the United Nations
special envoy and deputy secretary-general in charge of defense
and security affairs, left here Monday night for New York.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference before his departure, Benom said he
will report to U.N. chief Kofi Annan on the current situation in
Angola and on the investigation of the downed U.N. planes.
</P>
<P>
He told the press that the U.N. investigation team has located
the remains of the first plane in central Angola. However, he
said, the site had obviously been damaged and the black box which
recorded flight conditions was missing.
</P>
<P>
He noted that there was little possibility for any survivors
taking into consideration the big fire after the crash.
</P>
<P>
The envoy did not pointedly say that the plane had been shot
down.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Benom announced that the U.N. will send a
international team to the north of Huambo Province to search for
the second plane.
</P>
<P>
Huambo is currently under the control of the opposition
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA).
Reports from a Portuguese Radio said UNITA had issued a statement
saying it is willing to offer cooperation to the U.N. so long as
the communication channel is through.
</P>
<P>
Benom termed the current situation in Angola as "very
dangerous", but would not comment on whether the U.N. observer
mission will withdraw in due time.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government has confirmed that the U.N. mission has
been withdrawing its staff to the capital Luanda from various
places.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy arrived in Angola last Wednesday to investigate
into the two plane crashes before and after the new year. During
his stay in Angola, Benom held talks with President Eduardo dos
Santos from whom he obtained full support of the Angolan
government for the U.N. rescue mission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
