<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing to Issue Forecast of Air Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital is amongst
the world's top ten most polluted cities and now a daily forecast
of the pollution index is to be made by the Beijing
Meteorological Protection Bureau which will work closely with the
city's Environmental Protection Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The city authorities have put high on their agenda this year
the task of reducing air pollution, and an official said the
forecast will begin as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, Beijing -- along with the cities of Lanzhou,
Yinchuan, Xining and Hohhot in northeast China -- reported
seriously high levels of pollution resulting from large volumes
of suspended particles in the air.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that Beijing now has some 1.4 million motor
vehicles and the air pollution index has often been above
moderate levels because of tail gas emissions, coal-fired heating
and weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in Jinan, capital of east China's Shandong
Province, the city environmental protection bureau has advised
citizens to stay indoors wherever possible as it had serious air
pollution in the first week of this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
