<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, January 12 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Yugoslavian President Slobodan Milosevic on Monday
urged ethnic Albanian rebels in Kosovo to resume direct and
unconditional dialogue with the government, the official Yugoslav
news agency Tanjug reported.
</P>
<P>
He made the call when meeting with Knut Vollebaek, Norwegian
foreign minister and chairman of the Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE). He emphasized that negotiations
were the only way to solve the Kosovo crisis and autonomy within
Serbian republic was a realistic foundation for such a political
solution.(Yugoslavia-Kosovo )
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SAN VICENTE DEL CAGUN, Colombia -- The Colombian government
Monday called on the rebels to sit down at the negotiating table
to discuss the government's ten-point agenda on human rights and
a ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
The agenda was forwarded to the Revolutionary Armed forces of
Colombia in the second round of negotiations opened last Thursday
in San Vicente, one of the five central and southern
municipalities demilitarized last November. The ten-point
government proposal also aims to review the country's economic
and social structure, state and political reform and the
substitution of crops for drug-growers, whose crops and
processing labs are protected by the rebels.
(Colombia-Rebels-Truce)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- Albanian Prime Minister Pandeli Majko renewed the
appeal on Monday to ethnic Albanians in Serbia's Kosovo province
for speaking with one voice in settling the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Albanian government supports only a political solution
that favors the respect for the will of the Albanian people in
Kosovo as well as for international principles and rules, Majko
said in a meeting with Bujar Bukoshi, prime minister of the
self-claimed ethnic Albanian government in Kosovo. Such a
solution should be one acceptable not only to any individual
person or political force but also to all parties concerned,
Majko said. (Albania-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder on Monday
reaffirmed Germany's determination to promote the reform of the
European Union (EU) after a meeting between the European
Commission, headed by Jacques Santer, and German cabinet members
here.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was dominated by the consultation on the
restructuring of EU's financial spending, the reform of
agricultural policy and the slashing of Germany's financial
contribution to the EU. The EU has set March, when a summit is
held, as the deadline for completing its Agenda 2000 for internal
reforms. The agricultural policy reform is critical for financial
reform, which directly decides whether the EU can be successful
in expansion, said the chancellor. (Germany-EU)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- The Organization of American States (OAS) will
launch a mechanism this year to evaluate the anti-drug policy of
its member countries, OAS Secretary-General Cesar Gaviria said
here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Gaviria told the press that the OAS mechanism is designed to
counter the annual United States anti-narcotics certification
process and it will be supported by every country, including the
United States, and will create a climate of cooperation and not
confrontation. (OAS-Drug) 
</P>
</TEXT>
