<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Vehicle Sales Down in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's new vehicle sales
slumped by 15 percent in 1998, according to year-end figures just
released by the Kenya Motor Industry (KMI) Association.
</P>
<P>
The downturn to a total of 9,407 new vehicles is less than half
the number required to sustain a healthy and growing national
fleet, the Daily Nation newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The sales decline was attributed to the general economic woes,
high interest rates, tough taxation on company cars and dumping of
used imports.
</P>
<P>
The KMI bureau said passenger car sales have been particularly
hard hit and are down 21 percent, while the tough road conditions
have boosted four- wheel-drive vehicle sales, which were up three
percent.
</P>
<P>
The only other class which grew in 1998 was double cab pickups.
"These cab pickups used to be taxed like luxury cars," the KMI
bureau explained," but since the government started taxing them as
utility vehicles, several new models have been introduced and
sales have almost treble."
</P>
<P>
The KMI bureau added that the sales of double cab pickups grew
because they are among the most versatile, practical and
appropriate ones for Kenya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
