<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tianjin Expands Urban Power Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, January 12 (Xinhua) -- North China's port city of
Tianjin injected more than 1.3 billion yuan (about 158 million
U.S. dollars) into the construction of its urban electric power
network in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The funds were used to build and expand twelve 35-kilovolt
substations, and upgrade 475 low-voltage distribution networks
both at or under 10 kilovolts, according to local department
concerned.
</P>
<P>
During the 1991-1995 period, the city only had three
35-kilovolt substations. It was listed among the 25 cities by the
State Planning and Development Commission last year as the first
group which will be given considerable support for urban power
network construction.
</P>
<P>
To meet the demand of the city's economic development, the
region's power company decided to greatly improve the urban power
network between 1998 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
Within a year the power supply shortage has been eased, and
incidence rate of power failure reduced by 40 to 50 percent. This
has not only made residents' lives more convenient but has also
improved the city's ability to fight against natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
To further improve the power supply, the city will add one
million kilovolts to its current power supply of 2.6 million
kilovolts by the year 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Amway Salesmen Receive Certificates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government
recently issued certificates to Amway sales personnel who had
completed training which changed their working style form direct
sales to retailing.
</P>
<P>
This is the first batch of permits granted to foreign direct
sale companies, who have shifted to indirect sales after the
Chinese government's ban on the direct selling practice.
</P>
<P>
Following the ban last year, the 64 foreign direct sale firms
have turned to in-store selling either with or without salesmen.
To date, Amway, Avon, Mary Kay have changed their working
practices.
</P>
<P>
According to new rules salespeople working with these companies
must have certificates formally issued by the departments
authorized by the State Administration of Internal Trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
