<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Health Ministry Vows to Prevent Further Food Poisoning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- China's health authorities are
tightening up food safety regulations ahead of the Spring
Festival next month, the country's biggest annual holiday.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Health has issued an urgent circular urging
those responsible for food safety to check for contaminated lard
and suspicious-looking cooking oil.
</P>
<P>
In late December at least two died and some 200 people were
hospitalized in east China's Jiangxi Province, after being
poisoned with industrial animal oil which had been illegally sold
as cooking oil.
</P>
<P>
Seven suspects believed to be involved with the poisoning case
have been arrested by police, who have seized about 2,700 barrels
of the imported oil in south China's Shenzhen city.
</P>
<P>
"More barrels of this contaminated oil are believed to have
been sold to other regions outside Jiangxi and our investigations
will be widened," Chen Rui, an official with the Department of
Health Supervision under the Ministry of Health, told Xinhua
today.
</P>
<P>
"That particular case must be thoroughly investigated and
those responsible prosecuted. Checks should now also be made
throughout the food-processing industry, in restaurants and among
edible oil sellers," the circular stressed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
