<HEADLINE> Korda to Defend Australian Open Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Petr Korda of Czech Republic
Tuesday said he would not hide from the storm over his positive
drug test and would defend his Australian Open tennis crown here
this month, according to reports from Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
"I wanted to play in Australia because I haven't done
anything. Why should I hide? I don't have a problem standing in
front of anyone," said the 30-year-old Czech who failed a drug
test at Wimbledon last year.
</P>
<P>
After a player outcry, the ITF plans to challenge its appeal
committee for waiving a 12-month ban for Class One drug offences
provided under ITF, Association of Tennis Professionals and
Women's Tennis Association anti-doping rules.
</P>
<P>
A compulsory player ATP Tour meeting in Melbourne on Saturday,
with fines for players who do not attend, will thrash out Korda's
case.
</P>
<P>
Several players including Jim Courier and Jonas Bjorkman have
spoken out at the apparent leniency shown to Korda.
</P>
<P>
Korda begins his Australian Open buildup in the Colonial
Classic tennis tourney beginning in Melbourne on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
