<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Work Continues A Pace on Highway-Railway Bridge Across Hangzhou Bay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NINGBO, January 12 (Xinhua) -- A cross-sea bridge, the first
in China with roads and railway line on the same level, is under
intensive construction in the East China Sea.
</P>
<P>
Work has been completed on 60 percent of the bridge, 40
percent of the overpass on Daxie Island, as well as 20 percent of
the bridge approach on the bank of the Beilun port.
</P>
<P>
The bridge will have a total length of 3,723 meters. The
entire project consists of the main bridge, a highway approach
and a railway feeder line on Beilun bank, and an overpass on
Daxie Island. The first phase of the bridge will cost 370 million
yuan.
</P>
<P>
It is expected to be completed in late October and will be put
into service by the end of this year. By then, the annual freight
volume of the railway in the middle of the bridge will amount to
20 million tons, and the two-lane highways on both sides of the
railway will be able to allow 32,000 motor vehicles to pass
daily.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the bridge started in April 1997 and the whole
project will cost 430 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Daxie Island is one of the most suitable places on China's
east coast for an international bulk cargo center.
</P>
<P>
In November 1992, then Chinese Vice-President Rong Yiren, who
was chairman of the China International Trust and Investment
Corporation (CITIC), agreed to a large-scale land development on
Daxie. Upon approval of the State Council in March 1993, Daxie
Island has been given preferential treatment as an economic and
technological development zone.
</P>
<P>
The bridge is considered as an important infrastructure
project which will transform Daxie Island into a first-class port
and trade zone.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Sight First China Action" Helps Cataract Sufferers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The medical aid program Sight
First China Action helped 30,000 cataract sufferers regain their
sight in central China's Henan Province in 1998, according to the
latest statistics.
</P>
<P>
The total number of patients benefiting from this program has
increased to more than 50,000, according to the Disabled Persons
Federation of Henan Province.
</P>
<P>
Some of these people had been without their eyesight for as
long as 30 years.
</P>
<P>
The program has helped more than 50,000 cataract sufferers
receive operations, and more than 95 percent of them have
regained their sight.
</P>
<P>
Sight First China Action is jointly sponsored by Lions Clubs
International and the China Disabled Persons Federation. 
</P>
