<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crackdown on Financial Fraud For Orchard Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman for the People's
Bank of China, the central bank, warned today that the illegal
raising of investment capital for orchards or estates development
is strictly forbidden.
</P>
<P>
A number of orchards and estates developers have been found to
have engaged in such practices but their activities have not been
ratified by relevant, authorized departments.
</P>
<P>
The central bank spokesman pointed out that such practices
involve high levels of fraud and much risk as they claim
extremely high potential returns for investors which in fact can
not be realized.
</P>
<P>
"Investors have no control on the capital flow and management
and there is no guarantee on the safety of the investment, which
can easily lead to the money disappearing," he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said, the extremely high returns claimed by
these developers attracts large amounts of inward capital from
investors, which seriously disrupts the financial balance and
once the risks are realized the countryside's financial stability
will be affected.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that sales of overseas lottery tickets are
also prohibited, stressing that so far the Chinese State Council
has ratified only two kinds of lottery tickets: the China welfare
lottery tickets and the China sports lottery tickets.
</P>
<P>
He urged the public to learn more about the country's
financial laws and regulations to avoid being taken in by
fraudsters and thus also prevent financial risks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
