<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Get 2.9M Dollar Commodity Aid From Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh will receive 140
million taka (2.9 million U.S. dollars) commodity aid as
flood-related assistance from Germany under an agreement signed
between the two sides here Monday.
</P>
<P>
With this funding, medical supply goods and equipment will be
provided to health centers to improve and rehabilitate basic
health care facilities in Bangladesh, The Daily Star newspaper
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The amount was made available out of the budget of the German
Economic Cooperation and Development Ministry in the framework of
a special program earmarked for the flood calamities in
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, food aid operations with German funding of 227
million taka (4.68 million dollars) were launched and successfully
implemented through the World Food Program and the German
Technical Cooperation, the report said.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the German-Bangladesh negotiations on
development cooperation in Dhaka last December, the German
government committed another 140 million taka (2.9 million
dollars) within its 1998 financial assistance for Bangladesh for
urgent rehabilitation and reconstruction of rural roads and
markets.
</P>
<P>
Thus, in this connection with flood relief and rehabilitation,
Germany made available a total of over 500 million taka (10.3
million dollars) to Bangladesh as grant without payment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
