<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT January 12 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- European markets dropped sharply Monday on a wave of
profit-taking and Wall Street's fall at the impact of a weak U.S.
dollar and strong Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
The London stock market recorded a heavy fall as the FTSE 100
closed down 62.2 points to 6,085, even though the session had
been marked by frenetic merger speculation and takeover battles.
(Europe-Stocks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- The Dow Jones industrial average fell Monday after
a big rally last week but the technology-heavy Nasdaq index got
another big gain.
</P>
<P>
The Dow closed at 9,619.89, down 23.43. Earlier this
afternoon, The Dow suffered a 110-point loss, erasing all of the
105-point gains last Friday that pushed the blue chip index to
the record closing high of 9,643.32.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, the incredible rise in technology shares
including Intel and Dell Computer pushed the Nasdaq composite to
2,384.59, up 40.18 points, the 10th consecutive record high.
(US-Wall Street-Closing)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Crude oil prices rose 5 percent to a two-month high
on expectations for leaner supplies, after a key Nigerian
terminal was shut down by local protesters demanding a greater
share of oil revenue. (Dollar-Yen-Euro
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- The U.S. dollar fell to a 28 month low of 108.22
yen at one point on Monday, but became stronger against the
market's new comer euro.
</P>
<P>
The dollar was traded at 108.93 yen in New York late Monday,
against 110.93 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
However, the greenback rose to 1.1542 euro from 1.1554 euro on
Friday, the end of the first week the common currency of 11
countries of the European Union first entered into the market.
(Crude Oil-Surge)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Brazil, the world's most debt-burdened
developing country, will spend about 34.5 billion U.S. dollars s
ervicing its foreign debt and interest this year.
</P>
<P>
The Jornal do Brazil newspaper on Monday said that the
country's foreign debt due in 1999 were roughly equivalent to its
current hard currency reserves, the majority of which belongs to
the private sector. (Brazil-Foreign Debt)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thailand's exports are expected to grow four
percent to 56.6 billion U.S. dollars this year compared with 54.5
billion U.S. dollars last year, Deputy Commerce Minister Pravit
Rattanapien said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The anticipated exports figure this year would be very close
to the 55.9 billion U.S. dollars exports value registered in
1996, the year when Thailand began to experience a slowdown in
growth, Pravit said. (Thailand-Exports)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- International credit rating agencies are expected
to revise Thailand's sovereign ratings by mid-year in a major
move that would guide the country's future investments, finance
ministry officials said.
</P>
<P>
Moody's Investors Service now gives Thailand a "Ba1" rating,
just below investment grade status, while Standard and Poor's has
maintained a "BBB" grade, one step above the investment grade
threshold. (Thailand-Credit Ratings)- - - -
</P>
<P>
HONG KONG -- Hong Kong stocks rose 74.91 points, or 0.69
percent, to open at 10,797.61 on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The key Hang Seng Index gained 29.13 points, or 0.27 percent,
to close at 10,722.70 on Friday. (Hong Kong-Stocks-Open)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Indonesia's imports this year are predicted to
increase by 40 percent from the 1998 figure, but would be still
lower than the 1997 value which reached 46 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Imported goods would be dominated by industrial raw materials,
foods, and capital goods, said Amirudin Saud, chairman of the
Indonesian Importers Association (Ginsi). (Indonesia-Imports)
</P>
