<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Firm in Promoting Reform of EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 11 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder on Monday reaffirmed Germany's determination to promote
the reform of the European Union (EU) after a meeting between the
European Commission, headed by Jacques Santer, and German cabinet
members here.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was dominated by the consultation on the
restructuring of EU's financial spending, the reform of
agricultural policy and the slashing of Germany's financial
contribution to the EU. The EU has set March, when a summit is
held, as the deadline for completing its Agenda 2000 for internal
reforms.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural policy reform is critical for financial
reform, which directly decides whether the EU can be successful
in expansion, said the chancellor. Germany supported EU's enl
argement into eastern Europe. The first new members are not
expected to join before 2003.
</P>
<P>
Germany, which currently holds the EU presidency, has demanded
a cut in its net annual contribution to the organization of 22
billion marks (13 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Reform of farm subsidies, which devour half the annual EU
budget of about 100 billion dollars, remains key to revamping its
finances, Schroeder said. Bonn wants member states to start
paying more for their own farmers instead of sending the bill to
Brussels. This is opposed by France.
</P>
<P>
The reform of the EU should fairly consider the benefit and
interest of all its members, but "every member state must be
prepared to compromise," said Schroeder, who noted that this also
included Germany.
</P>
<P>
The chancellor also expressed his support for Santer's
commission which faces a vote on a motion of no-confidence on
Thursday. A two-thirds majority is necessary to force the
commission from office.
</P>
<P>
Bonn needed a strong commission to succeed in the reform of EU
finances by the summit, in order to pave the way for taking in
new members, stressed Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
The European Parliament in Strasbourg was due to open debate
Monday on corruption, fraud and mismanagement charges involving
the commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
