<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spain, Venezuela to Strengthen Trade Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Spanish Deputy Prime Minister
and Minister of Economy and Finance Rodrigo Rato said on Monday
Spain and Venezuela will sign a new financial protocol.
</P>
<P>
He made the announcement after meeting with visiting
Venezuelan President-elect Hugo Chavez to discuss ways to
strengthen bilateral trade ties.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Chavez also met with Spanish Foreign Minister Abel
Matutes. He pledged to open more opportunities for Spanish
investment in Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
Chavez, who started Monday in Madrid a tour of Europe, said he
wanted to transform Venezuela into an "authentic democracy"
through constitutional amendments.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, Spain's trade surplus with
Venezuela totaled 24 million U.S. dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Spanish exports to Venezuela range from mechanical and
electric machinery to automobiles, steel products and books,
while its imports from Venezuela are only crude oil and
aluminum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
