<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgarian Rose, Lavender Oil Sold Out in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAZANLAK, Bulgaria, January 11 (Xinhua) - Bulgaria for the
first time in ten years sold all its rose and lavender oil last
year, said Georgi Chaoushev, director of the Institute on Roses
in the central Bulgarian city of Kazanlak.
</P>
<P>
Some 400 kilograms of rose oil were sold by four Bulgarian
companies and the Plovdiv representation office of a French firm
at the prices from 3,650 to 4,000 U.S. dollars per kilogram. The
remaining stock of rose oil is no more than one kilogram, which
will meet this year's demands of the perfume industry, the senior
research associate said.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria's traditional rose oil industry, whose share of the
world market has slipped to 30 percent from around 70 percent in
1980s, has seen a considerable expansion in 1998. Its rose oil --
grown in the Valley of the Roses in the center of Bulgaria -- is
more expensive than rival products from China, Turkey and
elsewhere because of its high quality.
</P>
<P>
A total 15 tonnes of lavender oil at between 32 and 45 dollars
per kilogram have been sold to the traditional buyers from the
U.S. and France. For the first time, Greek and German traders
have taken part in the bids for the ethereal oils.
</P>
<P>
Last year's production of valerian and milk thistle will be
known by the end of January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
