<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Sets Up 815 Factories in Four Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
set up 815 factories and generated 700,000 jobs in the past four
years, the official Daily News reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Industrial Development Minister C.V. Gunaratne said that the
development projects initiated by the government had helped the
unemployment rate to drop from 14.5 percent in 1994 to 9.5 percent
last year.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a seminar for industrialists recently, Gunaratne
said the government will open 50 more garment factories, of which
25 would be located in the south of the country.
</P>
<P>
The garment industry occupies the first place in Sri Lanka
today and it is essential to maintain high standards in
manufacturing garments, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Sitawaka is expected to become a major industrial city in South
Asia when 77 factories are established there, said the minister,
adding that this industrial city will generate 50,000 jobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
