<HEADLINE> Venezuela to Seek IMF Backing for Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela's incoming
government led by President-elect Hugo Chavez will seek the
backing of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) for emergency
economic aid, said the Financial Minister Maritza Izaguirre on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Venezuela will have to present the IMF an economic program in
mid-March to obtain its support," said Izaguirre, who was named
Finance Minister by Chavez on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
She said the program, which will extend over this year and the
next to "get a seal of approval from the IMF", would help
reschedule the foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
Izaguirre said that she would start personal contacts next
week with the IMF, adding that IMF director Michel Camdessus
would travel to Caracas next month after Chavez is sworn in on
February 2.
</P>
<P>
She said that she would give priority to revamping the budget
on the basis of an average oil price of nine U.S. dollars a
barrel, adding that she would maintain a strict fiscal discipline.
</P>
<P>
Izaguirre said that the rescheduling of the foreign debt would
be necessary to curb the expected budget deficit of about eight
billion dollars if crude prices remained low. 
</P>
</TEXT>
