<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reasons, Results of Soaring Steel Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Increasing domestic steel
consumption boosted China's production to 94.48 million tons
between January and November last year, 9.4 percent more than the
same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
China Metallurgical News reported recently that the annual
production increase last year would reach 10 percent, which was
attributed to the central government's efforts to step up
domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
In October, for example, national fixed assets investment grew
by 28 percent, and the infrastructure investment growth was 30
percent.
</P>
<P>
Big steel consumers such as the machinery and household
electrical appliance sectors achieved marked growth toward the
end of the year as opposed to previous sluggish results.
</P>
<P>
In November last year, the growth rate for large and
medium-sized tractors was 70.5 percent; for automobiles 16.7
percent; and more than 30 percent for washing machines,
refrigerators and air conditioners.
</P>
<P>
The paper estimated the annual demand for steel products last
year was 110 million tons, a 4 percentage points increase over
1997.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, customs officials have firmly cracked down on the
smuggling of steel products, which has boosted demand for
domestic products.
</P>
<P>
However, there is great concern in the industry about the
negative effects of soaring production which, together with 10
million tons of imports, has resulted in probably 5 million tons
of unwanted steel products, in addition to those already in
storage.
</P>
<P>
"This has affected the supply-demand balance that was reached
in the previous period," the paper commented.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, by the end of October last
year half of the 6 million tons of additional steel produced was
sent into storage.
</P>
<P>
The overall market price of steel products started to drop fr
om November last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
