<HEADLINE> New OSCE Chief Urges KLA to Release Yugoslav Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 11 (Xinhua) -- The new head of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE)
claimed here Monday that it was "totally unacceptable" for the
ethnic Albanian guerrillas, the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA), to
hold Yugoslav soldiers as hostages.
</P>
<P>
"Taking hostages is totally unacceptable. OSCE has demanded
immediate release of hostages and maximum restraint. We have to
see an immediate release of the hostages if we should avoid a
major conflict," Norwegian Foreign Minister Knut Vollebaek told a
press conference after his meeting with Yugoslav Foreign Minister
Zivorad Jovanovic.
</P>
<P>
The two applauded the positive role the OSCE monitors in
Kosovo have been playing in search for a solution to the hostage
drama through political means.
</P>
<P>
Knut Vollebaek, who is on his first trip to the Balkans as new
chairman of the 54-nation European security watchdog, also
praised the constraint demonstrated by the Yugoslav government in
the drama.
</P>
<P>
The KLA captured eight Yugoslav army soldiers last Friday some
40 kilometers northwest of Kosovo's regional capital Pristina.
Monitors of the OSCE's Kosovo verification mission, backed by
pressure from the North Atlantic Treaty Organization and Russia,
were trying to persuade the KLA to free the soldiers and the
negotiations still continued. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
