<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slovakia's Inflation Rate Hits Historic Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Slovakia's inflation rate
dropped to 5.6 percent last year, the lowest since the former
republic of Czechoslovakia gained independence in 1993, according
to a report announced Monday by the Slovak Central Bank in the
capital, Bratislava.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Slovakia's economy was growing quickly, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Among the eastern European countries, Slovakia has one of the
lowest inflation rates.
</P>
<P>
In the early days of its independence, Slovakia's inflation
rate soared to 23.2 percent at the end of 1993, forcing the
government to take a series of measures, such as macroeconomic
regulation and monetary control, to curb
it.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate dropped sharply in recent years to 5.8
percent in 1996 and 6.1 percent in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Welcomes Release of Hostage by Colombian Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Foreign Minister
Lloyd Axworthy on Monday welcomed the release of Norbert Reinhart
who had been held captive by leftist rebels in Colombia for over
three months.
</P>
<P>
Reinhart, 49, an executive of Ontario-based Terramundo
Drilling, was released Saturday. Also released was a German
tourist, according to the Colombian anti-kidnapping authorities.
</P>
<P>
Reinhart surrendered himself to the Colombian rebels on
October 6 so that his employee Edward Leonard, taken prisoner on
June 24, could go free last year. His company was contracted by
Grey Star Resources, a Vancouver exploration company, to drill at
a Colombian site, the Canadian Press reported.
</P>
<P>
"These lengthy kidnappings, first of Edward Leonard and then
of Reinhart, were cruel and inhumane," said the Canadian minister
in a release. "The taking of innocent civilians in any
circumstances is unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
Axworthy expressed appreciation for the excellent cooperation
Canada received from the Colombian authorities, the Catholic
Church of Colombia, Grey Star Resources and the International
Committee of the Red Cross in seeking the release of Reinhart.
</P>
<P>
He also voiced satisfaction that the peace process between the
government of Colombia and the rebel forces is now underway.
Canada firmly supports this process and is ready to lend
assistance, if requested by the parties, to these difficult and
protracted discussions, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
