<HEADLINE> Milosevic Urges for Dialogue With Ethnic Albanians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 11 (Xinhua)-- Yugoslavian President Slobodan
Milosevic Monday urged ethnic Albanian rebels in Kosovo to resume
direct and unconditional dialogue with the government, the
official Yugoslav news agency Tanjug reported.
</P>
<P>
He made the call when meeting with Knut Vollebaek, Norwegian
foreign minister and chairman of the Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE).
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that negotiations were the only way to solve the
Kosovo crisis and autonomy within Serbian republic was a
realistic foundation for such a political solution.
</P>
<P>
He accused the Kosovo Liberation Army of attempting to
escalate the military conflict by taking eight Yugoslav Army
soldiers hostage.
</P>
<P>
The abduction was another example of terrorism by the KLA, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic urged again the OSCE to work for the release of the
eight soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The detention of the eight is the latest challenge to the
on-off ceasefire in Kosovo, where guerrillas are fighting for the
Albanian-majority province's independence from Serbia, the main
republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The eight soldiers were seized Friday as they were trying to
enter rebel-controlled territory. 
</P>
