<HEADLINE> Colombian Government Calls for Truce With Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN VICENTE DEL CAGUN, Colombia, January 11 (Xinhua) -- The
Colombian government on Monday called on the rebels to sit down
at the negotiating table to discuss the government's ten-point
agenda on human rights and a ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
The agenda was forwarded to the Revolutionary Armed forces of
Colombia (FARC) in the second round of negotiations opened last
Thursday in San Vicente, one of the five central and southern
municipalities demilitarized last November.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, a wave of killings launched last week by
pro-government death squads continued, leaving over 120 people
dead.
</P>
<P>
The ten-point government proposal also aims to review the
country's economic and social structure, state and political
reform and the substitution of crops for drug-growers, whose
crops and processing labs are protected by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
The government also includes in the agenda environmental
protection, the strengthening of the justice system and
anti-corruption measures.
</P>
<P>
It also wants to eradicate paramilitary groups, seeking the
international community's support for the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The FARC demanded the dismantling of the paramilitary death
squads, and put forward a general agenda including a political
solution to the conflict, the restructuring of the army,
congressional reforms, economic development with social justice,
taxes, energy resources, foreign relations and drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Colombian President Andres Pastrana said last Thursday there
would be no "banned issues" in the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The rebels have said that they are ready to accept a truce if
eight of its 10 proposals are accepted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
