<HEADLINE> Brazil Earmarks 34.5 Billion Dollars for Foreign Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Brazil, the world's
most debt-burdened developing country, will spend about 34.5
billion U.S. dollars servicing its foreign debt and interest this
year.
</P>
<P>
The Jornal do Brazil newspaper on Monday said that the cou
ntry's foreign debt due in 1999 were roughly equivalent to its
current hard currency reserves, the majority of which belongs to
the private sector.
</P>
<P>
The daily said that Brazil's private sector would spend at
least 21.6 billion dollars this year on its debts and interest.
</P>
<P>
The country this month had already earmarked over one billion
U.S. dollars to pay its foreign debts.
</P>
<P>
The central bank officially estimated that foreign debts
totaled 230 billion dollars at the end of 1998. In recent years,
Brazil paid every year about 30 billion dollars to its debtors.
</P>
