<HEADLINE> Lanzhou's Panda to Seek Mate in Chengdu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Two zoos in China are trying
to persuade a female and male panda to mate but zoologists says
the rare creatures, there are some one thousand left alive in the
wild, are very choosy.
</P>
<P>
The female panda, named Shu Lan, belongs to the zoo in
Lanzhou, the capital of northwest China's Gansu Province, and was
recently flown to the southwestern city Chengdu city, the
capital China's Sichuan Province, to check out male pandas that
are in the city's zoo.
</P>
<P>
Shu Lan is four and a half years old and Lanzhou zoo's only
giant panda and has never mated. The two zoos decided to
introduce her to the three males in Chengdu and are hoping that a
match will be made with one of them.
</P>
<P>
If she does conceive and gives birth, she and the cub will
return to Lanzhou.
</P>
<P>
However, even if Shu Lan doesn't take to any of the male
pandas, zoologists believe artificial insemination could be an
option. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
