<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Efforts to be Made to Expand Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- China will make accelerated
efforts this year to expand basic education, further reduce
illiteracy among young people and adults and help education
contribute more to regional economic growth, today's "China
Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based English newspaper quotes Education Minister
Chen Zhili as saying that her ministry will work together with
other ministries to help major universities develop research in
high technology and efficiently turn results and discoveries into
production.
</P>
<P>
A Plan on Education Development for the 21st Century, which
was worked out late last year, will be implemented this year.
</P>
<P>
The plan will provide guidelines within the next three to five
years for training higher-level talents and implementing the
nine-year compulsory education program among the population.
</P>
<P>
The country will help more than three million illiterate
people (aged 15-50) learn how to read and write.
</P>
<P>
More investment will be put into ethnic minority areas to
improve teachers' academic levels.
</P>
<P>
More than three-quarters of China's population have received
nine-year compulsory education. The number is expected to rise to
eighty percent by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Educational departments across the country will provide more
training opportunities for primary and middle school teachers, to
help improve their academic expertise, teaching skills and
professional qualities.
</P>
<P>
The move aims at shifting the previous examination-dominated
teaching method into a students' quality-oriented one.
</P>
<P>
Another important task is to develop vocational and adult
education programs, to help serve regional economic and social
development, and promote on-the-job and re-employment training
programs, the paper says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
