<HEADLINE> Thai Govt's Effort to Limit Rice Farming Fails </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government's effort to
limit second rice farming in the north this year in view of severe
drought has failed as a survey shows a more-than-two-fold increase
in the total area of cultivation.
</P>
<P>
The survey, made on December 30 last year by the Irrigation
Department and the Agricultural Extension Department, shows that
the total area of off-season rice farming in the north stood at
1.557 million rai (249,117 hectares) against a targeted limit of
720,600 rai (131,296 hectares), the Bangkok Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Agriculture Ministry's project to encourage farmers to turn
to other crops also appeared to have failed as only 1.252 million
rai (200.295 hectares) of a targeted 3.874 million rai (619,808
hectares) were being used for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
As of January 7, the water level was found to be low at 25 of
Thailand's 28 large reservoirs.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that only 31.7 percent of the water from the
country's seven major dams will be supplied this year for farming,
compared with 62.4 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the Interior Ministry, until January 8 this year
drought had already affected 232,469 families in 57 districts of
13 provinces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
