<HEADLINE> One-Third of Chinese Wine Producers Bankrupt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua)-- A third of China's 600 wine
producers have gone bankrupt in the past two years because of
over supply and fierce competition, reported a recent issue of
the Tianjin evening news.
</P>
<P>
In Tianjin, north China's biggest port city, half of the 38
wine producers were forced to shut down despite the market
economy that has taken deeper roots in China in the past years.
</P>
<P>
Wine production surged from 1996 and reached its zenith around
early Spring last year. Many liquor and soft drinks producers
turned to wine production, resulting in wine of inferior quality,
but these companies have mostly been forced out of business.
</P>
