<HEADLINE> Italy Rules Out Euro's Negative Impact on Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Italy's foreign trade will not
suffer because of the introduction of the euro, Italian Foreign
Trade Minister Piero Fassino said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the International Italian Chamber of Commerce,
Fassino said that such confidence comes out of the fact that
Italian companies have a very strong competitive capacity, as
demonstrated by last year's trade surplus.
</P>
<P>
Italy enjoyed a net trade surplus of 40 trillion lire (around
24.4 billion U.S. dollars) in 1998 despite the global economic
turmoil, ranking itself as the best performer among the
industrial countries in terms of trade surplus-GDP ratio,
according to Fassino.
</P>
<P>
Of the total exports, the minister said, 47 percent went to
the western European markets, 20 percent to eastern Europe, 12
percent to America, 7 percent to Asia and the remaining to other
small markets.
</P>
<P>
Italy is one of the 11 European countries which jointly
launched the euro on January 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
