<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar's Forest Area Down 7 Percent in 36 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar's forest area is
reducing year by year, dropping by 7 percent now as compared with
36 years ago, according to official statistics compiled by the
Forest Department under the Forestry Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The data of 1962 show that 57 percent of the country's total
area was then covered by forests. The percentage dropped to 51
percent in 1989 and then to 50 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Indiscriminate felling and cutting of trees in the forests for
fuel and burning of charcoal are said to be the main cause of
forest depletion in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The action has brought about ill effects such as the appearance
of barren hills in the areas covering northern Myanmar down to
southern Ayeyawaddy division, the transformation of central
Myanmar into a tropical region and depletion of tidal forests
resulting in landslides and scarcity of marine products.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has worked out projects for greening the regions, under
which measures for reforestation, conservation of both reserved
and non-reserved forests, re-establishment of fuel-wood
plantations and tidal forests are being taken.
</P>
<P>
Under the project for using firewood substitute fuel, stoves
using them are produced and production and sale of briquettes are
the means being applied in the tropical regions. Trees for use as
firewood are planted in tidal forest areas.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has imported briquette making machines and arrangements
are being made to build briquette factories in Sagaing, Mandalay
and Magway divisions.
</P>
<P>
To use as firewood substitutes to prevent forest depletion,
briquettes, micro-wave ovens and agricultural wastes are being
applied. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Army Denies Report of Arms Supply to Sri Lankan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Thai army has denied that
arms smugglers are using Phuket, southern Thailand, as their base
to supply arms to Tamil rebels in Sri Lanka, The Bangkok Post
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
But, Gen. Surayud Chulanont, the army chief, confirmed Monday
that arms smugglers were using sea lanes in the Gulf of Thailand
and the Andaman Sea to ship war weapons from Cambodia and Myanmar
to Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
However, Surayud rejected allegations that some senior Thai
Army officers were involved in arms smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Surayud was referring to Monday's report in the
English-language Nation newspaper which quoted senior Sri Lankan
foreign ministry and army officials in making the allegations.
</P>
<P>
The army chief said he was confident that no Thai military
officers were involved in arms smuggling, and promised harsh
punishment if any of them was ever caught and proven guilty.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Adm. Thira Haocharoen, the navy chief, maintained
that the Thai military had no policy to support anti-government
movements in any country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
