<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, January 12 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGDHDA -- Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Said Al-Sahaf said
at a press conference here on Sunday that United States and
Britain are using the United Nations Security Council and Saudi
Arabia and Kuwait in committing aggression against Iraq on
December 16-19.
</P>
<P>
He said that the two countries views the United Nations
Security Council as a pair of shoes, when they like it, they put
on them and when they do not like it they take off.
(BC-Iraq-Press Conference)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia Sunday called for the immediate release of
hostages held by Albanian rebels in the Yugoslav province of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"Moscow is demanding the immediate and unconditional release
by Albanian guerrillas of all the hostages they have seized," the
Russian Foreign Ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The appeal came after reports that Yugoslav federal forces
were moving to rescue the eight Serb policemen held by the Kosovo
Liberation Army (KLA). (Russia-Kosovo-Hostage)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Yemen has promised not to use force to rescue a
kidnapped oil worker, a British official said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Yemen confirmed that a British oil worker, hired by a U.S.
firm, was kidnapped in Yemen on Saturday, only two weeks after
four hostages were killed in an attempted rescue.
</P>
<P>
The four, three Britons and one Australian, were killed during
a shoot-out between militant Muslems and Yemeni troops.
(Britain-Yemen-Hostage)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM-- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
reiterated here on Sunday that Israel will not allow the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) to declare an independent
state in May this year.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu told a weekly cabinet meeting that the Israeli
government intents to implement its decision concerning Israel's
response to an unilateral declaration of Palestinian statehood or
the division of Jerusalem. (Israel-Palestinian)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Chief U.N. weapons inspector Richard Butler said
Monday that U.N. weapons inspections would not be dead and he
would not resign.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a conference on arms non-proliferation, Butler
said, "UNSCOM (U.N. Special Commission) was not dead." He
predicted there might be a compromise in the U.N. Security
Council of future inspection operations in Iraq, which were
halted after four-day bombing raids against Iraqi targets by U.S.
and British missiles.
</P>
<P>
He expressed confidence that the Security Council would
maintain the organization although some changes might be
required. (Butler-UNSCOM) 
</P>
