<HEADLINE> Riots, High Risk to Investment in Indonesia: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Minister of
Investment Hamzah Haz has called on the public to prevent the
occurrence of mass riots that will deteriorate the country's image
abroad and further batter the investment climate.
</P>
<P>
He said that the mass riots that broke out in Karawang, which
is located 60 kilometers northeast of Jakarta in a rice-growing
area, last Friday pose a high risk to investment activities in
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Two people were shot dead and eight others were injured after
security officers opened fire to prevent the mob from attacking
shops in Karawang. It was reported that six police posts, Karawang
police station and Kota police station were vandalized by the mob.
</P>
<P>
The minister cited three things as the impact of the riots.
First, it would reduce the activities of realized investment;
secondly, new investment due this year will be under threat of
collapse; and thirdly, those with investments of around 5 billion
U.S. dollars that have been running for one year are more than
likely not to extend their investment period.
</P>
<P>
He said that the trend in the drop in investment proposals and
realized investments by foreign investors was seen throughout
1998.
</P>
<P>
Last year saw 60 percent of foreign and domestic investments
canceled due to the deteriorating security climate in Indonesia,
the minister was quoted by the Indonesian Observer Tuesday as
saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
