<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tianjin to Build More Anti-Flood Works </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The north China metropolis of
Tianjin will spend about 1.1 billion yuan to construct and
rebuild anti-flood works in urban areas of the city over the next
three years.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin is located at the lower reaches of many rivers through
which the water from Beijing and Hebei Province rushes into Bohai
Bay, so Tianjin has the arduous tasks of combating floods on the
rivers and containing the sea tides. But the city has a low
flood-combating capability due to limited investment in the
construction of anti-flood works in the past years.
</P>
<P>
Information from the Tianjin Municipal Water Conservancy
Affairs Bureau said the money will mainly be used to finance
construction of seven major projects, including consolidating
levees along the main stream of the Haihe River, enabling them to
sustain the flow of flood waters at a speed of 800 cubic meters
per second, and constructing more embankments to hold back the
sea tides.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, more foreign loans will be introduced to co
nstruct an advanced anti-flood information network to facilitate
flow of information and decision making in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Five of the projects will start construction this year and
will require an investment of 350 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin had major floods in 1939, 1963 and 1996 and suffered
heavy losses during the first two floods. It is estimated that
the new anti-flood facilities of the past few years have brought
more than 17 billion yuan in economic benefits.
</P>
<P>
Major flooding on the Yangtze River, China's longest, and on
the Nenjiang and Songhua rivers in northeast China last summer
caused severe losses to the Middle Kingdom. Many localities seem
to have learned a lesson from the last year's flooding and have
increased investment for constructing anti-flood works in a bid
to gain an edge over future floods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. House: Evidence Supports Charges Against Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. House of
Representatives insisted Monday that evidence against President
Bill Clinton "overwhelmingly supports" both charges -- perjury
and obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
In papers filed with the Senate, the Republican-controlled
House said that "perjury warrants conviction and removal" from
office of a duly elected president under Senate precedents.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who went on trial in the Senate on January 7, stands
accused of two articles of impeachment -- perjury and obstruction
of justice, in connection with his effort to conceal a sexual
relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky. He
is the second president in U.S. history to be subjected to a
trial, after Andrew Johnson in 1868.
</P>
<P>
The House's papers were filed in advance of opening arguments,
set for Thursday in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Clinton's lawyers decided to forgo filing a
motion seeking to dismiss the case at its very inception,
although officials suggested they would make that motion after
both sides had finished opening arguments.
</P>
<P>
The House decided against filing any immediate motions, as
well, although lawmakers are certain to seek permission from the
Senate to call witnesses to testify at the end of the period in
which both sides present evidence.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Monday, the White House said that the impeachment
charges against Clinton should be dismissed, saying that the
accusations "do not permit the conviction and removal from office
of a duly elected president."
</P>
<P>
"The charges in the articles do not rise to the level of `high
crimes and misdemeanors' as contemplated by the Founding Fathers
and they do not satisfy the rigorous constitutional standard
applied throughout our nation's history," Clinton's attorneys
said in a response to the Senate's trial summons.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has acknowledged that his behavior with Lewinsky was
improper, but "the charges in the two articles of impeachment do
not permit the conviction and removal from office of a duly
elected president," his lawyers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
