<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TV Rights Battle Kicks Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 11 (Xinhua) -- One of the most crucial matches
in the history of British sport will be played out on Tuesday -
in the unlikely setting of a London courtroom.
</P>
<P>
According to the BBC report on Monday, the multi-million pound
battle is between the English Premier League and the Office of
Fair Trading (OFT).
</P>
<P>
The case hinges on whether the present 743 million pound
broadcasting contract between the Premiership, BSkyB and the BBC,
which expires in 2001,is in the public interest.
</P>
<P>
But sports minister Tony Banks has already warned of the
"damaging implications" for the game if the OFT wins the case.
</P>
<P>
Banks said he agreed with the chairman of the Football Task
Force, David Mellor, who claimed the grass-roots of the sport
could lose up to 50 million pounds as a result of a court ruling
in favour of the OFT.
</P>
<P>
"If the OFT finds against the football authorities there will
be profound damaging implications for the whole structure of
football in this country," Banks said.
</P>
<P>
"I endorse entirely the views put forward by the Task Force
and I hope the court will take such comments into consideration."
</P>
<P>
The case will open at the Restrictive Practices Court and is
expected to last as long as four months.
</P>
<P>
The OFT claims that the league is operating as a cartel in
brokering the joint TV deal with the two broadcasters on behalf
of 20 clubs.
</P>
<P>
It insists that consumers are being cheated because the
Premier League is artificially inflating the cost of football and
restricting fans' access to watching games on television. Only 60
of the 380 Premiership games are televised live.
</P>
<P>
John Bridgeman, Director General of Fair Trading said: "Any
other business acting in this way would be subject to competition
law and I see no reason why the selling of sport should be
treated differently."
</P>
<P>
However, the Premier League argues that the current system is
working well, earning clubs between 5 and 10 million pounds each
per season.
</P>
<P>
It believes an end to the collective selling of rights would
create a chasm between the top league clubs and the rest and risk
destroying the structure of the competition, possibly sparking a
breakaway by the elite clubs.
</P>
<P>
The Premier League also fears that victory for the OFT could
mean more media companies attempt to takeover top clubs, leading
to a shift of power from the league and clubs to corporate giants.
</P>
<P>
The value of soccer rights to television companies was
dramatically underlined last year when BSkyB tabled a 623 million
pound bid for Manchester United, the most profitable and best
supported club in the Premier League.
</P>
<P>
The bid is currently on hold pending an investigation by
Britain's competition authorities.
</P>
<P>
A bid by cable TV company NTL for Newcastle United is expected
if the BSkyB/Manchester United deal goes through. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
