<HEADLINE> Manchester United Expects FA Cup Crowd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 11 (Xinhua) -- English Premier League club
Manchester United expect to have a capacity crowd for their FA
Cup fourth round tie against Liverpool despite being ordered to
close the North Stand at Old Trafford following Sunday's power
failure.
</P>
<P>
According to the BBC, Trafford Council, the licensing
authority for the stadium, said the club must prove all problems
with the electricity supply have been solved before any
spectators will be allowed into the stand.
</P>
<P>
The Cup game does not take place until January 24 and United
hope to discover the cause of the problem soon.
</P>
<P>
The start of United's match with West Ham was delayed for 45
minutes while engineers tried to restore power to the ground.
</P>
<P>
Problems resurfaced following the game when emergency lighting
went out on four stairways and thousands of fans were kept
waiting as they field out through two emergency exits.
</P>
<P>
An extra 128 United staff and 86 police officers were deployed
in the stand to ensure everyone left safely.
</P>
<P>
The club insists supporters were not in any danger and staff
had rehearsed for such a scenario.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Ken Ramsden said: "There was a loss of lighting in
the four conventional stair towers, but the main lighting in the
concourse itself and the two emergency stair towers had full
lighting.
</P>
<P>
"For those people exiting under the control of our staff,
there were delays but that was because it was a well-ordered job."
</P>
<P>
But a movie tribute to United legend Sir Matt Busby which was
filmed at the ground went off without a hitch.
</P>
<P>
Fans remained silent for half-a-minute before power was lost,
during scenes shot for a biopic of George Best.
</P>
<P>
The club is co-operating with electricity company, Norweb, in
a full investigation into the cause of the power failure and does
not believe there is any threat to the FA Cup fourth round tie.
</P>
<P>
"We expect to have the matter resolved within a couple of
days. We are very confident that we will play the Liverpool game
as scheduled and ticket sales are going ahead as usual," said Ra
msden. 
</P>
</TEXT>
