<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Deal Benefits Small Teams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 11 (Xinhua) -- NBA officials, in drafting
the new collective-bargaining agreement, did not want to turn the
league into one of haves and have-nots.
</P>
<P>
Throughout the negotiations, it was a priority of those
involved to avoid ending up with a settlement that would favor
the large-market teams and allow them to buy up the big-name
players and dominate NBA.
</P>
<P>
The intent was to keep the Milwaukees, Sacramentos and
Minnesotas of the league solvent and competitive. NBA
commissioner David Stern thinks the league succeeded with the new
agreement.
</P>
<P>
"It gives 29 teams the opportunity to compete," said Stern.
"It emphasized continuity of roster. Hopefully, players will be
encouraged to maximize their income and do it with the teams that
they previously played with.
</P>
<P>
"It give well-managed teams the opportunity to have a return
on their investment. We want the fans in all NBA cities, when the
exhibition season is about to begin to have a sense or to be able
to have a sense over some period of years, that there's an
opportunity for their teams to compete and possibly win. That is
very important. We think this leads us in that direction."
</P>
<P>
The new system of annual salary increases allows a player to
make more money if he stays with the same team. If a "Larry Bird"
player re-signs with his own team, he may sign a seven-year
contract with annual raises of 12.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
If a player goes to an other team, he will be limited to a
six-year deal with annual raises of 10 percent. The thinking is
that this will encourage players to re-sign with their own teams
even if they are in samll markets.
</P>
<P>
Stern said it was hoped that the new deal would increase
franchise values around the league which would also benefit the
samll-market teams. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
