<P>
NEW YORK, January 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. dollar dropped to
108.93 Japanese yen Monday from 110.93 yen last Friday, a
28-month low for the U.S. currency.
</P>
<P>
During the trading day at the New York Foreign Exchange,
the dollar fell to 108.22 yen, the lowest since August 26, 1996.
It was trading at more than 147 yen last August.
</P>
<P>
The dollar lifted when the U.S. treasury denied a report that
Washington was happy with a weaker dollar because that would
make it easier for U.S. companies to sell their goods in Japan.
</P>
<P>
After the Japanese yen started soring against the dollar
last Thursday, Chris Widness, economist at Chase Manhattan Bank
in New York said that yen's rise will hinder any economic
recovery in Japan this year because the stronger Japanese
currency will make Japanese exports more expensive, reducing
its overseas profits.
</P>
<P>
But the dollar gained ground Monday against most major
currencies. The European single currency, euro, slipped to
1.1542 dollars from 1.1554 Friday.
</P>
<P>
The dollar was also trading at 1.6946 German marks, up
from 1.6929 Friday and at 5.6818 French francs, up from 5.6766.
</P>
</TEXT>
