<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium Hopes to Shorten Euro Transition Period </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Brussels, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Belgium has expressed hope to
see euro notes and coins in 2001 instead of 2002 as legally planned,
officials said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Belgium Finance Minister Jean-Jacques Viseur told Monday's
local newspaper De Morgen that the EU should look again at
introducing euro notes and coins on March 1 or October 1, 2001,
rather than as planned on January 1, 2002.
</P>
<P>
However, a European commission spokesman said at a news briefing
that the current legal situation is defined in a regulation which
was adopted on May 3 last year. "To change that regulation would
require a further European Commission proposal and for that to be
unanimously adopted by the 11 countries in the euro zone," he said.
</P>
<P>
When asked about possibility of shortening of the transition
period, the spokesman said that though much shorter period is more
desirable, the commission would not make proposal at this stage.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Belgian Finance Ministry spokeswoman said Viseur
will put forward the question at a meeting of EU finance ministers
next Monday and ask the European Commission to examine whether it
is possible.  
</P>
</TEXT>
