<HEADLINE> Adams Returns to Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Tony Adams has successfully
completed his comeback after seven weeks out with a back injury.
</P>
<P>
Arsenal and England defender Adams came through the
Gunners'reserve-team outing against Northampton reserves showing
no adverse reaction to the problem which has kept him out of
action since November 25.
</P>
<P>
The inspirational center-back picked up a booking as he
skippered an experienced side in a 2-0 defeat at Sixfields.
</P>
<P>
The Gunners, who also boasted Nigel Winterburn, Christopher
Wreh, Nelson Vivas and Remi Garde among their second string, were
undone by goals in either half by Kevin Wilson and Christian Lee.
</P>
<P>
Adams picked up his yellow card in the 63rd minute after
tangling with Wilson on the edge of the box.
</P>
<P>
The Highbury favourite was penalised in the first half for a
tackle from behind on Lee, and when the resulting free-kick was
not cleared properly, Wilson finished cleanly from the edge of
the box.
</P>
<P>
For the second goal, Adams was left vainly appealing for
offside as Wilson flicked the ball over the top for Lee to round
Stuart Taylor. Despite the result, Adams' return is a boost for
both Highbury boss Arsene Wenger and England coach Glenn Hoddle.
</P>
<P>
Wenger, masterminding the Gunners' defence of the Double is
already without several key players and center-back Steve Bould
suffered a knee injury on Saturday which may require surgery.
</P>
<P>
Hoddle too, would welcome back the inspirational Adams for the
friendly against World champions France on February 10 and the
Euro 2000 qualifier with Poland on March 27.
</P>
<P>
Adams in now likely to step back into the first team for
Saturday's game against Nottingham Forest at the City Ground.
</P>
</TEXT>
