<HEADLINE> Atkinson Takes over at Nottingham Forest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Ron Atkinson will begin to work
at Nottingham Forest as manager next weekend without any fear of
failure.
</P>
<P>
His appointment as the club's boss until the end of the season
was confirmed in a statement to the Stock Exchange on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The former Manchester United, Aston Villa, Sheffield
Wednesday, Coventry and West Brom boss had been installed as
favorite for the job following the sacking of Dave Bassett last
week.
</P>
<P>
Peter Shreeves has been named as his number two after working
with Atkinson in a similar capacity at Wednesday and they face
the task of saving the club from relegation.
</P>
<P>
"I would think it's a marvelous challenge, not one to fear.
Ron achieved the same at Coventry when they were in a tight
situation," said Shreeves.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged that confidence among the players was "fairly
low" but added: "If there's anyone who can do the job better than
Ron, the name doesn't come to mind easily."
</P>
<P>
One of English football's most flamboyant characters, Atkinson
has developed a reputation as a "Red Adair", who can get teams
out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
But he faces a particularly tough task at the City Ground.
</P>
<P>
Forest were humbled 4-0 by another of Atkinson's former clubs
Coventry at the weekend and are now rooted to the bottom of the
table after a dismal run of 18 Premiership games without a
victory.
</P>
<P>
The lowest point of the campaign came last week when they were
knocked out of the FA Cup by First Division side Portsmouth - a
result that cost Bassett his job.
</P>
<P>
The club's statement to the Stock Exchange read: "Nottingham
Forest has appointed Ron Atkinson as manager of Nottingham Forest
Football Club.
</P>
<P>
"Mr Atkinson will take up his appointment as manager prior to
the home game against Arsenal on Saturday 16th January 1999."
</P>
</TEXT>
