<HEADLINE> Former Tazanian President Attends Burundi Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Former Tazanian President
Julius Nyerere, the international mediator on Burundi, was among
participants on Monday at the start of the two-day talks aimed at an
end to the civil war and aid economic development in the African
country.
</P>
<P>
The closed-door meetings at the U.N. headquarters in New York are
being attended by regional, donor and U.N. officials. The talks were
jointly organized by the U.N. Department of Political Affairs, the
U.N. Development Program and the Canadian Government.
</P>
<P>
Officials in Nairobi, Kenya, said over the weekend that Nyerere,
who met with U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on Monday, would
likely recommend to East African leaders that they suspended
sanctions against Burundi when they meet in Arusha, Tazania, on
January 18.
</P>
<P>
Regional states, including Kenya, Tazania, Uganda, and Rwanda,
imposed an economic and trade embargo on Burundi after retired Major
Pierre Buyoya took power in an army coup in July 1996.
</P>
<P>
Their main condition was that Buyoya starts talks with Hutu rebels
engaged in a bloody conflict with the country's Tutsi-dominated army
in which 150,000 people have died since 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
