<HEADLINE> Crude Oil Prices Surge on Production Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Crude oil prices rose 5 percent
to a two-month high on expectations for leaner supplies, after a
key Nigerian terminal was shut down by local protesters demanding
a greater share of oil revenue.
</P>
<P>
The shutdown of Royal Dutch/Shell Group's Forcados oil terminal
is contributing to a 300,000 barrel-a-day drop in Nigerian
production, or about 0.4 percent of world supply. The disruption
followed a report last week that U.S. inventories had their
biggest drop in 18 years.
</P>
<P>
February crude oil rose 37 cents, or 2.8 percent, to $13.44 a
barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange, the highest price
since November 13. Crude prices are down 17 percent from a year
ago, though prices have gained in eight of the past 10 sessions.
</P>
<P>
In London, February Brent crude oil rose 31 cents, or 2.6
percent, to $12.04 a barrel, on the International Petroleum
Exchange. The February Brent contract expires on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
However, traders expect that Nigerian crude oil will arrive
back on the market soon.
</P>
<P>
Expectations for rising prices also are being fed by historical
pricing trends, according to market analysts.
</P>
<P>
When prices broke through $13.25 a barrel, which was last
week's high, crude rallied all the way to $13.75 a barrel, said
traders who use charts and graphs to predict pricing trends.
</P>
<P>
Whether the rally continues into tomorrow will hinge on the
results of a report on the size of U.S. inventories by the
American Petroleum Institute, traders and analysts said. The API
is to release its report for the week ended January 8 after
trading Tuesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
