<HEADLINE> Competition Makes EU Insurance Industry Slim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Brussels, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Growing competition within the
15-nation European Union (EU) single market has made EU insurance
industry smaller, data available here Monday shows.
</P>
<P>
The data from Eurostat, the EU's statistical office, said the
number of economic actors is decreasing while the financial
indicators show only a slight upward trend in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Eurostat said the total number of direct insurance
enterprises in the EU fell by 3.36 percent between 1996 and 1997,
from 3099 to 2995, while most EU countries reported a drop with
the biggest being in Greece (-11.18 percent), Spain (-9.73
percent), France (-7.22 percent) and Denmark (-5.71 percent). And
in contrast, Ireland recorded the largest EU growth of 10.89
percent, followed by Sweden with 8.15 percent.
</P>
<P>
"The fall in the number of enterprises is most likely a result
of mergers to face growing competition," says Eurostat, adding
that since the liberalization and deregulation of the insurance
markets through related EU directives, Europe has been increasing
competition, and the introduction of the euro will eliminate a
further barrier between 11 euro zone countries: Austria, Belgium,
France, Germany, Italy, the Netherlands, Luxemburg, Spain,
Portugal, Ireland and Finland.
</P>
<P>
Currently, enterprises are reacting at different levels in
order to meet increasing competition and maintain or extend their
market share. As a result, the number of mergers and acquisitions
is increasing while efforts are being made to lower operational
costs and maintain or lower prices, says Eurostat.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
