<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 11 (Xinhua) -- European markets dropped sharply
Monday on a wave of profit-taking and Wall Street's fall at the
impact of a soft U.S. dollar and strong Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
The London stock market recorded a heavy fall as the FTSE 100
closed down 62.2 points to 6,085, even though the session had been
marked by frenetic merger speculation and takeover battles.
</P>
<P>
Banks, pharmaceuticals, oil and telecom shares fell after
rising sharply in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
A fresh wave of corporate activity, including a tie-up between
British American Tobacco and Rothmans International helped
sentiment, but failed to stop the slide.
</P>
<P>
Frankfurt shares fell back after early gains as profit-takers
took over. At the close the Xetra Dax was 104.04 points lower at
5,265.47.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that big portfolio managers were adopting a more
pan-European approach to equities after the launch of the euro,
and that the reshuffling could continue until mid-February.
</P>
<P>
Paris shares fell back on profit-taking after last week's
strong run. At the close the Cac 40 index was 43.52 points lower
at 4,201.90. 
