<HEADLINE> U.S. Disappointed by Cool Cuban Response to Initiatives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 11 (Xinhua) -- The United States Monday
expressed disappointment over Cuba's cool response to U.S.
initiatives designed to increase cash flows to ordinary Cubans and
expand people-to-people contact.
</P>
<P>
"It is hard not to be disappointed by the initial public
response the Cuban officials have made that could make it less
likely that the benefits of this arrangement to the Cuban people
would be made possible," State Department spokesman James Rubin
said.
</P>
<P>
Rubin noted that without the acquiescence or cooperation of the
Cuban government, some of Clinton's initiatives cannot be
implemented.
</P>
<P>
"We trust that upon reflection, the Cuban government will
choose to cooperate on these measures where their concurrence is
needed," he said.
</P>
<P>
The administration hopes the government of Cuba does not impede
the workings of these arrangements to the detriment of the Cuban
people, he added.
</P>
<P>
Last week, U.S. President Bill Clinton proposed direct mail
service between his country and Cuba, and also more U.S. residents
eligible to wire cash donations to needy Cuban families.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. organizations also would be allowed to send
funds to non-governmental organizations on the island and the
charter flights would be increased.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also announced expanded cultural ties in education,
sports and other spheres while food sales and the sale of farm
inputs would be permitted on a limited basis.
</P>
<P>
However, the measures were dismissed by Cuban officials as a
"public relations maneuver," stressing they would have little
effect on Cuba's economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
