<HEADLINE> Greece Denies Plans for Tripartite Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Greece Monday denied that there
were plans for a tripartite meeting between the U.S., Greek and
Turkish leaders in Washington in April to discuss the relations
between Athens and Ankara as well as the protracted Cyprus
problem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing, Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas said that a tripartite meeting between U.S.
President Bill Clinton with the Prime Ministers of Greece and
Turkey had not been brought up and had not been examined.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the tripartite meeting would take place on
the occasion of the summit of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) in Washington in April.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey have been at odds for decades over their
disputes in the territorial waters, air space limits and the
delimitation of the continental shelf in the Aegean Sea and the
Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has for years been trying to mediate between Greece
and Turkey to resolve their differences, but has made little
progress.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe that with the recent cancellation of
plans by Cyprus to deploy the Russian-made S-300 anti-Aircraft
missiles on the divided island, opportunities have come for Greece
and Turkey to improve their strained relations and for the Greek
Cypriots and Turkish Cypriots to re-start their inter-communal
talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
