<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Finance Minister on EU-Asia Finance Ministers Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 11 (Xinhua) -- The search for ways to stabilize
currency exchange rates and world economic issues top the agenda
at a meeting of European and Asian finance ministers in Frankfurt
this week, German Finance Minister Oskar Lafontaine said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The present economic developments in Europe clearly show the
world economy is also our fate and that we need world economic
cooperation to avoid extreme down-turns of economic development in
the future," said Lafontaine at a Bonn news briefing.
</P>
<P>
European Union (EU) and Asian finance ministers would discuss
extreme exchange rate shifts and the high mobility of short-term
capital in Asia which was causing dislocation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ways to stabilize Japan's banking system would also be on the
agenda at the meeting of finance ministers from the 15-nation EU
and 10 Asian states from January 15 to 16, said Lafontaine.
</P>
<P>
But, above all, the meeting would be dominated by developments
in the world economy and recommendations to stabilize
international finance markets and exchange rates, he said.
</P>
<P>
Lafontaine said the meeting was aimed at bringing
"step-by-step" progress but he declined to name any concrete
policy goals.
</P>
<P>
"The economic disturbances we have prove that stable exchange
rates are necessary," he said. "This is basically undisputed
because otherwise one would have to be for strongly shifting
exchange rates. And this would in effect mean one was pleading for
investment insecurity and the major loss of jobs."
</P>
<P>
Lafontaine said that aside from Asia, other countries like
Mexico had had to pay a great deal to make up for exchange rate
shifts.
</P>
<P>
In a barb evidently aimed at the United States, he said, "You
know my experience is that some (states) begin to shift only when
they notice certain changes in the world economy are also
impacting on them. That's how I would put it diplomatically."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0299 </DOCNO>
