<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak PM Reiterates Endeavor to Curb Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif has reiterated his endeavor to curb terrorism in the
country, particularly in Karachi, the country's largest city,
despite receiving dire threats directly.
</P>
<P>
"All my experience convinces me that unless we can pull out the
roots of violence from our soil we can make no progress," Sharif
said in a letter written to the Attorney General on Sunday asking
him to project his government's point of view before the court in
the most effective manner.
</P>
<P>
The Attorney General read this letter on Monday before a
seven-member bench of the Supreme Court hearing the petitions
against the establishment of military courts. The Supreme Court
has stopped the execution of death sentences by the military
courts till it decides their validation.
</P>
<P>
"We can advance neither in the field of economic development,
nor of social betterment and nor of cultural and educational
advancement," the prime minister said, adding the nation will
constantly remain mired in poverty, backwardness and ignorance.
</P>
<P>
"Others will advance and we will lag behind. If we are to
progress we have to break the mould of lawless killings and
eradicate the vortex of violence. This is not merely necessary but
essential," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that at a time when the government is poised to resume
economic growth it is facing the renewed threat of terrorism and
sectarian violence.
</P>
<P>
"Waves of blood have been submerging our fair and tranquil land
from time to time. We emerge from one blood-bath only to be
drenched in another. We seek to eradicate the virus of bloodshed
only to see another manifestation emerge, in a stronger and more
virulent form," he said.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the recent wave of violence the Prime Minister
wrote, "You are aware that for the past two years the tide of
violence has been ever increasing. I have no desire to criticize
the ordinary courts. I know that they operate under difficult
circumstances."
</P>
<P>
"But how many terrorists have been convicted and executed in
the past two years? Thousands have been killed, but how many have
been punished?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
Concluding the letter the prime minister said that he wants to
assure everyone concerned that he respects the functioning of the
ordinary courts.
</P>
<P>
"But there is a grave and real emergency in the country which
has been upheld by the Supreme Court. I do not wish to discuss any
legal or constitutional issues of which the Supreme Court is the
best judge. Nor do I desire to seek to influence the court's
deliberations in any manner in a pending case," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
