<HEADLINE> Singapore's Economic Outlook Remains Uncertain: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 11 (Xinhua) -- A senior Singapore official
said here Monday that his country's economic outlook for this year
remains uncertain.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the commissioning of a new 400 kilo
volt transmission system at the Labrador substation, Minister of
Trade and Industry (MTI) Lee Yock Suan said "at this point of
time, it is very difficult to be certain how we are going to
perform this year."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the prediction by some analysts that the economic
crisis here is bottoming out, Lee said it is still difficult to be
certain of such a prediction, adding the current economic
situation appears mixed.
</P>
<P>
The minister said his ministry is keeping to its original
forecast of between minus one percent and plus one percent growth
in GDP this year.
</P>
<P>
The forecast was first announced in November 1998 and
reiterated by Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong in his New Year
Message. Singapore's GDP grew 1.3 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Lee said "we depend very much on the external environment, the
U.S. market, -- whether it holds up, the European market, what the
Japanese do and of course what our neighbors do."
</P>
<P>
The 400 kilo volt transmission system is part of the islandwide
power grid's project to distribute electricity in greater bulk to
its consumers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
