<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan's Exports Plunge by 12.4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's exports plummeted
by 12.4 percent to 3.803 billion U.S. dollars during the first
half of the current fiscal year as compared to exports worth 4.342
billion dollars during the corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
According to an announcement by the Federal Bureau of
Statistics (FBS) Monday, the imports also decreased by 19.6
percent to 4.397 billion dollars as compared to imports of 5.472
billion dollars during the first half of last fiscal year
</P>
<P>
Traders have attributed the decline in exports to recession in
international market during the period while they have attributed
the plunge of imports to measures taken by the State Bank of
Pakistan (SBP) and Ministry of Finance.
</P>
<P>
The SBP placed 30 percent cash margin requirement on imports
except a few items last July. However, it reduced the margin to 20
percent on January 10. In addition to that it also introduced a
dual exchange rate mechanism under which the dollar became
costlier for importers.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the steps by SBP somehow also helped the
government narrow the trade deficit which has come to 594 million
dollars during the first half of the current fiscal year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
