<HEADLINE> Turkish Parliament to Vote on New Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Bulent
Ecevit said here Monday that the parliament is expected to hold a
vote of confidence for the newly established 56th government on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after submitting the cabinet list to
President Suleyman Demirel, Ecevit said that the government
program will be read at the parliament on Tuesday, and the
parliament debates on the program will be held on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, ousted Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz handed over his
post to Ecevit.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit, who served as deputy prime minister in the Yilmaz
cabinet, said that he worked in harmony with Yilmaz during the
55th government for 18 months.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit has worked as prime minister for three times since 1974.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his gratitude for Yilmaz's support for the
formation of the new government, saying that they will work
together afterwards.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Yilmaz said he believed that Ecevit and his
government will carry Turkey to general elections on April 18
successfully.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit, 73, had failed to form a government last December. He
was reassigned after independent lawmaker Yalim Erez also failed.
</P>
</TEXT>
