<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soaring Yen Hurts Japan's Economy, Journal Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 11 (Xinhua) -- The soaring Japanese yen
against U.S. dollar last week does not signal some newfound
economic strength in Japan but hurts its exports, The Wall Street
Journal said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The yen's rise will hinder any economic recovery this year in
Japan, the Journal quoted Chris Widness, economist at Chase
Manhattan Bank in New York, as saying. "dollar weakness is Japan's
problem," Widness said.
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday, the dollar fell to 111.04 yen, a 27 month low
after Eisuke Sakakibara, a high-ranking Japanese official said
that he was worried about soaring U.S. stock market. The plunge
for dollar became a major topic on that day when a research team
at Alliance Capital Management Corp. gathered for a strategy
session in New York.
</P>
<P>
The Journal said that a rising yen makes life tougher for
Japanese exporters, as locally produced goods become more costly
in world markets. At a time when Japan is counting on exports to
help lift the economy out of its swoon, the best thing for
Japanese multinationals is a weaker yen, not a weaker dollar, it
said.
</P>
<P>
commenting on the repatriation of Japanese funds from the
United States to enjoy better yields, the Journal said Japanese
bond yields have suddenly jumped to more than 2 percent from less
than 1 percent. but the bond prices have plummeted. And with the
expected issuance of mountains of new debt to stimulate the
moribund economy, Japan's bond market still looks risky to many
market watchers.
</P>
<P>
"In other works, it's yet another measure of Japan's weakness
that its bond yields are suddenly more attractive," it said.
</P>
</TEXT>
