<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Architect Francois Spoerry Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 11 (Xinhua) -- French architect Francois
Spoerry, who designed the lagoon city of Port-Grimaud on the
French Riviera and a similar residential district in New York, the
United States, died on Monday at the age of 86.
</P>
<P>
A former resistance fighter during World War II, Spoerry began
his career before the war. He became internationally known for the
1960s designing of Port-Grimaud in accordance with what he called
``soft architecture'' combining human works with natural
surroundings.
</P>
<P>
He was also the designer of the Liberty Port luxury housing
complex in New York on the west bank of Hudson River facing
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
Spoerry also designed housing complexes in Spain, Turkey and
Mexico. 
</P>
</TEXT>
