<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Pledges to Work Hard on the Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 11 (Xinhua) -- The United States is determined
to "work very hard to seize the opportunities" created by Cyprus
President Glafcos Clerides' decision regarding the S-300 missiles
issue, U.S. ambassador to Cyprus Kenneth Brill said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus contracted for Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft missiles
in 1997 in a bid to boost its defense, a move rejected by Turkey,
which threatened to launch preemptive strikes if the missiles
were deployed in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Clerides decided late last December to cancel the deployment of
the missiles in Cyprus after consultations with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after his meeting with Clerides, Brill said there is a
lot of hard work to be done to move forward on the Cyprus issue
and opportunities have to be seized through consistent work.
</P>
<P>
He called for support for the initiatives taken by United
Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Brill said that security is a core issue which must be
addressed in a comprehensive way for the ultimate solution.
</P>
<P>
He pledged U.S. support for the work of Ann Hercus, chief of
mission of the U.N. Peace-keeping Force in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that the U.S. supports a bicommunal, bizonal
federation in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island after a
failed pro-Athens coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with
Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
