<HEADLINE> EU Sees HK's Post-handover Period Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 11 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) said
in its first annual report on Hong Kong that the Chinese
territory's basic rights, freedoms and autonomy have been broadly
upheld, although it is suffering its worst recession for decades
after being severely battered by the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
After the report was published here on Monday, Sir Leon
Brittan, vice-president of the European Commission, said the
success of Hong Kong's post-handover period in such adverse
economic conditions is a tribute to the determination of both Hong
Kong and Beijing to safeguard the former's wide-ranging autonomy
as enshrined in the Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR). This bodes well for the future, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Full respect for "one country two systems" is the best
guarantee of Hong Kong's future prosperity, and thus its ability
to support China's own domestic reforms, Brittan said.
</P>
<P>
"The commission is greatly reassured by the overwhilming degree
of freedom enjoyed by the media, the legal system and ordinary
people in Hong Kong, even though some isolated cases have raised
some questions," the EU commissioner said.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the EU's executive body, pointed out in its
report that an effective enforcement of the "one country two
systems" concept is fundamental to Hong Kong's lasting stability
and prosperity, which in turn will benefit the EU and other world
partners who have for many years enjoyed a dynamic trade and
investment relationship driven in part by Hong Kong's independent
free market economy.
</P>
<P>
China will also benefit from the international financial
center's prosperity and stability, the report said. For China, "a
robust, globally integrated Hong Kong is a powerful buttress to
its own economic reforms".
</P>
<P>
The EU therefore, the report said, sees the upholding of the
Hong Kong SAR's autonomy, within the "one country two systems"
concept, as a central plank of its policy towards the territory
and a major component of its relationship with China as a whole.
</P>
<P>
In April last year, the EU set about upgrading its links with
the SAR by adopting a policy document entitled "The European Union
and Hong Kong: beyond 1997". Based on the document, the EU
commission undertook to produce an annual report on relations
between the EU and Hong Kong. Today's report is the first of such
kind. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
