<HEADLINE> Tobacco Research Meeting Opens in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 11 (Xinhua) -- A four-day regional meeting on
tobacco control started Monday in Nyanga, east Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The meeting aims to set research priorities for eastern,
central and southern Africa and identify critical economic,
social, environmental, legal and health problems that are brought
 bout by tobacco production and consumption, the Zimbabwe News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The meeting has drawn more than 20 participants from 14
countries. They are mostly researchers, policy makers and
community activists of health, agricultural economics, social
science, environment and law.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony, Zimbabwean Minister of Health and
Child Welfare Timothy Stamps said tobacco consumption and
production are escalating rapidly in developing countries as
governments and societies in general did not seriously consider
the use of the crop which poses serious health hazards.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco is known to cause about 25 diseases, including lung
cancer, heart diseases, strokes, emphysema and other chronic lung
diseases, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Tobacco control needs to be more widely recognized as a
development priority," the minster stressed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
