<HEADLINE> Japan Presents Plan for Israeli Pullout from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Foreign Minister
Masahiko Komura Monday presented to the Israeli government a plan
for the withdrawal of Israeli troops from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Komura presented the plan to Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon during their meetings
in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that the four-point plan demands the
adoption of Resolution 425 of the United Nations Security Council,
which calls on Israel to pull out its troops from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The plan proposes that Israeli and Lebanese governments discuss
concrete steps of withdrawal, adding that peace moves should not
have any preconditions.
</P>
<P>
The plan calls for international support for the withdrawal and
help in stabilizing the situation in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
It also calls for a resumption of Israeli-Syrian peace talks
after the withdrawal is completed and offers Japanese mediation to
all the parties involved.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said that the plan exactly matched the Israeli
policy in the Israeli-Lebanese negotiations, adding he hopes to
renew the peace talks with Lebanon and Syria if he wins the early
elections on May.
</P>
<P>
Sharon also hailed the ideas as "impressive," saying that
he welcomes Japanese mediation in the Israeli-Lebanese talks.
</P>
<P>
The radio said that Komura had shown the plan to senior Syrian
and Lebanese officials during his visits in the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Before his tour in Israel, Komura has visited Egypt, Lebanon,
Syria, Jordan, and the Palestinian areas.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a buffer zone in south Lebanon in 1985 and has
refused to withdraw from the region unless the Lebanese government
agreed to negotiate security arrangements to protect northern
Israel from guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese government rejected the Israeli proposal, noting
that the U.N. resolution calls for unconditional Israeli
pull-out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
