<HEADLINE> Annan on Ties Between UNSCOM and U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 11 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan stressed on Monday that he has no evidence of ties
between the United Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM) and the
United States as the media had charged.
</P>
<P>
Annan made the statement upon arriving at the headquarters of
the United Nations this morning.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief said the statement he issued last week is
factual and he would hope that this issue could be put to rest.
</P>
<P>
Annan said he did not think the issue was Richard Butler,
Executive Chairman of UNSCOM in charge of dismantling Iraq's
weapons of mass destruction, and he did not think the issue was
UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
"In the scheme of this, we are dealing with much larger issues
about compliance of Iraq and stability in the region that we
should focus on," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I have absolutely no evidence and I think Butler's statement
has been forthright and the U.S. itself has said they give him
support that he required for his work," the Secretary-General
added.
</P>
<P>
Washington Post and Boston Globe reported last week that UNSCOM
had help the United States intelligence agents to spy on Iraq,
which further put UNSCOM's future in question.  
</P>
</TEXT>
