<HEADLINE> Chinese, Tanzanian FMs Sign Cooperation Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Foreign
Minister Tang Jiaxuan and his Tanzanian counterpart Jakaya Kikwete
signed three agreements here Monday to boost bilateral
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreements, China will grant Tanzania some two
million U.S. Dollars' worth of assistance to improve the
rehabilitation of water supply facilities in the central city of
Dodoma.
</P>
<P>
China also agreed to donate 100,000 U.S. Dollars for emergency
food aid to help Tanzania alleviate the worsening food shortage
caused by natural disasters and drought.
</P>
<P>
On the cultural field, China and Tanzania agreed to boost
exchanges of cultural delegations, arts troupes, books and
reference materials between libraries as well as visiting scholars
and experts.
</P>
<P>
The exchange of information and cooperation between the news
media is also encouraged.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Chinese Foreign Ministry donated some office
equipment worth of 20,000 Dollars to the Tanzanian Ministry of
Foreign Affairs and International Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Signing these agreements, Tang and Kikwete expressed
satisfaction with the development of bilateral cooperation under
the new regional and international situation.
</P>
<P>
They said both governments encourage Chinese businessmen to
invest in Tanzania to increase local production in various fields.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers pledged to explore new ways to enhance
bilateral cooperation especially in the economic and trade sector.
</P>
<P>
Tang, who is on his fourth leg of an African tour which has
brought him to Egypt, Kenya and Uganda, is expected to visit some
Sino-Tanzanian joint ventures on Tuesday before departing for his
last stop in Zambia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
