<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Record Number Refuse to Serve in German Armed Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 11 (Xinhua) -- A record number of men refused to
serve in the German military last year by declaring themselves
conscientious objectors, the defense ministry said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Deutsche Presseagentur(dpa) reported, in 1998 a total of 171,657
men refused to do their military service - the highest number since
the German armed forces were reestablished after World War II in 1955,
the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
This figure beat the previous record of 160,494 conscientious
objectors set in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The defense ministry said there was no single cause for the new
record. "It's a big mix of individual motives," said a ministry
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Under Germany's constitution anyone has the right to refuse to bear
arms in war. Those who exercise this privilege normally perform civil
service and the many young men working in hospitals, old-age homes or
with the handicapped have become an important source of cheap manpower
for the German social welfare state.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Rudolf Scharping said despite the number of
conscientious objectors the armed forces still did not have a problem
getting the required number of new recruits each year.
</P>
<P>
About 163,000 young men were conscripted into the German armed
forces in 1998 for their 10-month mandatory service, said the
spokesman, adding, however, that the figure should not be
misunderstood even though it was lower than the number of
conscientious objectors.
</P>
<P>
"We only call in as many conscripts as we need and last year we
did not need more," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Bundeswehr, Germany's armed forces, has a total strength of
340,000 troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
