<HEADLINE> White House Not to Dismiss Senate Impeachment Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton's lawyers will not make a motion seeking dismissal at the
outset of his impeachment trial, Democratic sources said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The sources, who asked not to be named, said the president's
lawyers still planned to make such a request but would save it
until after both sides could give their opening presentations.
Democratic lawmakers had suggested the delay in deference to the
desire of senators to open the trial in bipartisan fashion.
</P>
<P>
The president's lawyers, meanwhile, were responding to the
Senate trial summons and declaring they would present a defense
for articles of impeachment accusing the president of perjury and
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
Officials said they expected the first response to be short, 11
or 12 written pages, making clear their intention to aggressively
contest the charges and to argue the evidence doesn't warrant the
removal of the president.
</P>
<P>
Both House prosecutors and White House lawyers had until the
end of the day to present motions, but Democratic sources said the
White House would file no motions Monday.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who went on trial in the Senate on January 7, stands
accused of the two articles of impeachment -- perjury and
obstruction of justice -- in connection with his effort to conceal
a sexual relationship with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky. He is the second president in U.S. history to be
subjected to a trial, after Andrew Johnson in 1868. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
