<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 2,200 Rwandans Flock Back from DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 11 (Xinhua) -- More than 2,200 Rwandans who
had crossed to Masisi Region, in northeastern Democratic Republic
of Congo (DRC) at the beginning of the armed Hutu insurgency last
year have started to flock back home, the Rwanda News Agency (RNA)
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
''Since January 1st up to the10th, we have registered 2,253
returnees. They are in poor condition and need urgent
assistance,'' the RNA quoted Ramazani Barengayabo, the Mayor of
Rwerere as reporting.
</P>
<P>
More returnees continued to arrive from Masisi, which was the
hotbed of the Hutu extremists behind the waves of insecurity that
characterized the northwest Rwanda in the recent past. Over 100
returnees were registered on Monday, the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
Rwerere commune is located in the northeast of Gisenyi, near
the border with the DRC. It is amongst the communes in northwest
Rwanda which paid a heavy tribute to the armed insurgency.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, Rwerere commune shelters more than 53,000 residents
who turned their heels against the armed Hutu extremists, as the
pressure by the government army and the political mobilization are
gaining ground.
</P>
<P>
''The resettlement of these people is gaining momentum,''
Barengayabo told RNA. Nineteen construction sites have been
selected, and the works have already started,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
The returnees interviewed by RNA affirmed that they had been
held hostages by the Hutu extremists -- former Rwandan government
soldiers (ex- FAR) and '' Interahamwe'' -- which had established
bases in Masisi.
</P>
<P>
''They were telling us the government in Rwanda is massacring
Hutus, that we should join the struggle to liberate the country,''
said one returnee.
</P>
<P>
Most of the returnees said they decided to return to Rwanda,
after they had reassuring messages from President Pasteur
Bizimungu who, with his entire cabinet, visited Rwerere and other
parts of northwest Rwanda early last month.
</P>
<P>
It is said that these returnees, some of whom were involved in
attacks, have revealed arms caches they left behind before
crossing to Masisi.
</P>
<P>
The returnees claimed that the Hutu extremists have been
inflicted a heavy blow by the Congolese rebels fighting to
overthrow President Laurent Desire Kabila.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
