<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Meets Argentine President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
met Argentine President Carlos Menem Monday at the White House
with hopes that the meeting would put the public attention more on
his job than on his impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and Menem planned to discuss trade, climate change,
Bosnian peacekeeping and U.S. policy toward Iraq, said P.J.
Crowley, the spokesman for the National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the meeting, Clinton told reporters the United States
and Latin American nations "have turned a page in our history"
over the past 10 years, as leaders abandoned dictatorship for
democracy and became a force for peace in other areas of the
world.
</P>
<P>
"Our future has never been brighter," Clinton said. "This year,
we are a hemisphere at peace, essentially without international
conflicts, moving beyond historic animosities to discover new
opportunities."
</P>
<P>
The United States is Argentina's second-largest trading partner
after Brazil. Menem wants to talk about trade and efforts to
fight drug trafficking and international terrorism, and filling
the vacant U.S. ambassadorship to Argentina.
</P>
<P>
They would also discuss climate change and encouraging more
developing nations to embrace the idea of reducing greenhouse gas
emissions.
</P>
<P>
Argentina played host to a U.N. conference on climate change in
November, and agreed then to adopt a target on reducing emissions.
</P>
<P>
On Clinton's impeachment trial, Menem stated unequivocal
support for Clinton before leaving Argentina, saying Congress was
"going against what the people of the United States want" by
continuing the impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders last met in October at the annual meeting of
the International Monetary Fund in Washington, and Clinton paid a
state visit to Buenos Aires in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
Menem is scheduled to leave office later this year, although he
has not ruled out another bid for office.
</P>
<P>
The administration designated Argentina a non-NATO ally in
1997, a status that allows access to surplus military equipment.
Argentina is the only Latin American country to have the title.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
