<HEADLINE> China Ups Its Mission in Zanzibar to Consulate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 11 (Xinhua) -- The government of the
People's Republic of China decided Monday to upgrade its
diplomatic mission in Zanzibar of Tanzania from consulate to
consulate general to further develop bilateral friendly
relations.
</P>
<P>
According to an agreement signed here by visiting Chinese
Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan and his Tanzanian counterpart Jakaya
Kikwete, Tanzania agrees to such a move and retains its right to
establish its own consulate gneral in China in the future.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian government agreed to provide all necessary
assistance and convenience to the Chinese Consulate General in
Zanzibar in the performance of the consular functions.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed to properly handling consular matters
between them in the spirit of friendly consultation, and in
accordance with international practice as well as international
laws, including the Vienna Convention on Consular Relations.
</P>
<P>
A highly self-ruling part of the United Republic of Tanzania,
Zanzibar, which consists of two main islands in the western Indian
Ocean, has a population of about 800,000, mostly Muslims.
</P>
<P>
China established its diplomatic relations with Zanzibar a few
days after the latter got independence from the Sutan King rule on
January 12, 1964.
</P>
<P>
The Consul General Wang Jikui, who speaks fluently the local
Kiswahili language, expressed his willingness to do his best to
upgrade the friendly bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Tang, who is on his fourth leg of an African tour which has
brought him to Egypt, Kenya and Uganda, is expected to visit some
Sino-Tanzanian joint ventures on Tuesday before departing for his
last stop in Zambia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
