<HEADLINE> Russia Calls for Talks between Belgrade and Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Russia Monday called for
immediate direct talks between Belgrade and Kosovo Albanina
rebels, according to the Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
Russian Foreign Ministry's spokesman Vladimir Rakhmanin told a
news conference that Russia "believes the international community
should help this process in every possible way".
</P>
<P>
He noted that Kosovo settlement will be among problems to be
discussed at talks between Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov
and his counterparts from the U.S., France, Poland, Cuba, Sweden,
Israel and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Russia, seriously concerned over the attack by Kosovo
Liberation Army gunmen on Yugoslav and the seizure of eight
servicemen last Friday, cannot have terrorists and extremists
disrupt the process of political settlement in Kosovo, Lakhmanin
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Moscow resolutely condemns that action and regards it as a
crying manifestation of terrorism. Russia hopes that the OSCE
mission in Kosovo will continue talks in order to successfully
free the hostages, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Lakhmanin also called for head of the U.N. Special
Commission on Iraq (UNSCOM) Richard Butler to resign amid a row
over reported links between UNSCOW and Western special services.
</P>
<P>
He said that "We have repeatedly noted in the past that
Butler's activity had discredited the Special Commission."
</P>
<P>
On the Iraq problem Lakhmanin said Russia hopes Iraqi leaders
will display a responsible approach to the problem of relationship
of Iraq with the United Nations and neighbouring countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
