<HEADLINE> Lebanon to Apply Full-Scale Administrative Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Despite opposition from former
government leaders, Lebanese President Emile Lahoud vowed Monday
to launch a full-scale administrative reform campaign to fight
corruption.
</P>
<P>
"The state will continue what it has started on administrative
reform, which should include every public employee, rather than
being confined to those on first-rank positions," Lahoud said when
meeting with parliament members.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud took office from his predecessor Elias Hrawi last
October and a new cabinet was formed at the end of 1998, headed by
prime minister, Salim Hoss.
</P>
<P>
On swearing in in the parliament, Lahoud vowed to save the
country from economic crisis and political instability through a
dramatic administrative reform.
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday, the cabinet decided to remove around 20 senior
civil servants from their posts in an attempt to invigorate
performance, stop financial squandering, and check corruption.
</P>
<P>
However, the move sparked an outcry from the opposition
spearheaded by former Prime Minister Rafik Hariri and his
political partner Walid Jumblat, a minister in Hariri's government.
</P>
<P>
Hariri accused the government of seeking "political revenge
and grudges," saying the campaign was politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
Among those fired on charges of mismanagement, seven are
believed to be close to Hariri, who had upheld premiership since
1992, in the aftermath of the country's 1975-1990 civil war.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud defended the government measures, saying the officials
were dismissed according to reports issued by the Civil Service
Council and inspection bodies.
</P>
<P>
Press reports said that the government is expected to announce
a new round of dismissals at the weekly cabinet session on
Wednesday which will also include another of Hariri's allies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
