<HEADLINE> Visa Restrictions Barrier Between EU, HK: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Current visa restrictions
continue to act as a burdensome barrier to business between Europe
and China's Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR), the
European Union (EU) said in its first annual report published here
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
By July this year, 49 countries were giving Hong Kong visa-free
access, of which just the Britain and Ireland are within the EU,
while Hong Kong granted visa-free access to 170 countries and
territories, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the EU's executive branch, has also
noticed that the local business community, as well as European
companies operating in the SAR, have expressed strong desire to
see free business travel available between Hong Kong and the EU.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the EU holds that there is a strong case to be made
for giving Hong Kong more generous treatment, noting the Chinese
territory's determination to operate a secure and efficient
immigration and passport control system in Hong Kong. However, the
report said the existing procedures are perceived as costly,
burdensome and unfriendly to business.
</P>
<P>
"The SAR has the authority to issue passport and other travel
documents, as well as applying its own immigration controls. While
the commission has no direct responsibility for visas, it strongly
supports Hong Kong's efforts to secure visa-free access to the EU.
The SAR government continues to see this as the most important
issue in the territorty's relations with Europe," the report said.
</P>
<P>
But the commission believes a generous attitude from 15 EU
member states would further underpin Hong Kong's status as a
separate customs territory with its own immigration policy, a key
pillar of the "one country, two systems" formula initiated by
former Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
