<HEADLINE> Muluzi Invites Tanzanian Businessmen to Invest in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Malawian
President Bakili Muluzi Monday invited Tanzanian business people
to invest in his country and promote bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
"I can assure you that your investment in Malawi would be safe
and profitable," Muluzi said while addressing the business
communities of the two countries at the Sheraton Hotel in Dar es
Salaam.
</P>
<P>
He said the Malawian government will create a conducive
environment for Tanzanian businessmen, like providing loans to
them and fighting against the evil of corruption.
</P>
<P>
Muluzi, himself a businessman before he was elected the
president of Malawi in 1994, said the two countries should set up
cross-border fairs, and intensify cooperation in transport,
telecommunications, energy, tourism and agriculture sectors.
</P>
<P>
The Malawian president said African countries should strengthen
economic cooperation through organizations like Common Market for
Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) and Southern Africa
Development Community (SADC), especially when trade globalization
becomes a trend. He cited the example of the launching of Euro
currency.
</P>
<P>
"We should work together, otherwise we will be left out," he
said, stressing that African products must be of quality if they
want to be competitive in the world market.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, the Malawian president visited Murzah Oil
Mills Ltd, a local edible oil company which started commercial
production in July of 1997. It is using refined palm olein
imported from Malaysia for production.
</P>
<P>
Muluzi said he is very impressed by the company, which has an
investment of eight million U.S. Dollars and a production capacity
of 30,000 metric tons of refined edible oil per annum.
</P>
<P>
Aruna Chalam, the Financial Controller of Murzah Oil Mills Ltd,
told the president his company is operating at 30 percent of full
capacity at present. Additional machinery is being installed to
facilitate the production of other soft oils like soybean and
sunflower seeds.
</P>
<P>
The company management has expressed wishes to export edible
oil to Malawi, which imports edible oil from other countries
through Dar es Salaam port.  
</P>
</TEXT>
