<HEADLINE> Conservative Blames Khatami Supporters for Murders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Iranian conservatives appeared
making a counter-offensive by accusing supporters of President
Mohammad Khatami of being behind the mysterious political killings
over the past months.
</P>
<P>
Rowhollah Husseinian, head of the Islamic Revolution Documents
Center where important archives are kept, claimed those involved
in killing liberal figures "were from the left-wing faction and
convinced supports of Khatami."
</P>
<P>
The conclusion was drawn from a "political point of view," he
told the evening newspaper Kayhen.
</P>
<P>
The conservatives, believed to have the support of the supreme
leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, and moderates led by Khatami are
embroiled in a fierce power struggle as the country's economic
situation further slid.
</P>
<P>
A number of liberal advocates and writers were murders over the
past months and Khatami ordered a thorough investigation. Last
week, the Intelligence Ministry owned up that some of its agents
were involved in the crimes.
</P>
<P>
However, Husseinian alleged that the killers were from certain
religious groups and the main culprits were Khatami's supporters.
He did not provide any evidence to support his accusation.
</P>
<P>
He said the killings were an attempt to seize the Intelligence
Ministry that has been under conservative control, and part of a
left-wing scheme to "take over organs of state power one by one."
</P>
<P>
"As I know," he said, "the opportunist left-wing forces were
planning a scenario to take over the Information (Intelligence)
Ministry" - they have indeed put several deputy ministers and
other officials in it.
</P>
<P>
He urged the intelligence minister, Qorbanali Dorri Najafabadi,
to stand against the pressure and to dismiss those sent in by the
left-wing faction.
</P>
<P>
Some reports said that Khatami has vowed to sack Najafabadi
after the revelation of the involvement of intelligence agents in
the political killings.
</P>
<P>
The conservative daily Tehran Times reported Sunday that
Najafabadi decided not to quit after the supreme leader blamed
foreign hands in the murders.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei told the Friday prayers congregation that he could not
accept that those murders took place "without a foreign scenario
behind them." 
</P>
</TEXT>
