<HEADLINE> Security Council Meets on Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council on Monday met behind closed doors to discuss the latest
situation in Sierra Leone as West African countries are stepping
up mediation to defuse the crisis in the West African
English-speaking country.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council was briefed by the U.N. Secretariat on the
current situation in Sierra Leone, Celso Amorim, president of the
15-nation Council for the month of January, said.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council is expected to consider a report on Sierra
Leone by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who said that "Sierra
Leone has suffered a serious setback."
</P>
<P>
In his report to the Security Council, Annan recommended the
extension of the mandate of the U.N. Observer Mission in Sierra
Leone (UNOMSIL) for another two-month period, until March 13.
</P>
<P>
"The future of UNOMSL now appears much less clear than it did
only a matter of weeks ago," said the U.N. chief, who also intends
to reduce the number of military observers, retaining in Conakry,
capital of neighboring Guinea, a small number who would return to
Sierra Leone when conditions permit.
</P>
<P>
UNOMSIL groups 56 military observers and medical servicemen,
they were forced to leave for Guinea in the wake of the rebel
advance in Freetown, capital of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Also on Monday, two West African foreign ministers flew to
Freetown on Monday and had talks with President Ahmad Tejan Kabbah
and commanders of a regional force battling rebels in the city,
witnesses were quoted as saying in Freetown.
</P>
<P>
Amara Essy of Ivory Coast and Joseph Kokou Koffigoh of Togo
launched a fresh drive for a ceasefire six days after the rebels
captured large areas of Freetown. 
</P>
</TEXT>
