<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Law Lords to Hear Pinochet Petitions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Three of Britain's most senior
judges will on Wednesday hear applications from the Chilean
government to intervene in the re-hearing of the case of former
Chilean leader Augusto Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
The three law lords will also consider petitions from human
rights body's, as Amnesty International and Human Rights Watch,
the House of Lords said.
</P>
<P>
After Wednesday's hearing, seven law lords, who are sitting as
the country's highest court, are scheduled on January 18 to
re-hear arguments whether Pinochet is entitled to immunity from
arrest as a former head of state.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the law lords set aside a ruling they made in
November that Pinochet had no sovereign immunity. The former
ruling had cleared the way for the start of the 83-year-old
general's extradition proceedings to Spain.
</P>
<P>
Lawyers for Pinochet successfully argued that the case should
be re-heard as one of the original five judges had close links
with Amnesty International.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet is currently living under police guard in a rented
mansion near London, awaiting the outcome of the extradition
battle in the English courts.
</P>
<P>
The retired general was arrested at a private hospital in
london on October 16 while recovering from a back surgery. A
Spanish court accused him of responsibility for the deaths and
disappearances of more than 3,000 people during his 1973-90 rule
and wanted him to be extradited to Spain to face charges.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet said last month in a london court that he would not
recognize any court outside Chile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
