<HEADLINE> Mozambican Senior Fighters Urged to Contribute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
More in Development
</P>
<P>
MAPUTO, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican senior fighters
were urged Monday by President Joaquim Chissano contribute more in
promoting economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony of the second national meeting of the
Mozambican senior combatants' conference opened in Chimoio City in
central Mozambique Monday, Chissano said the law on senior
combatants to be mapped out, will, in consideration of the
specific condition of the country, guarantee to offer aid to the
senior combatants in the war for independence, the Mozambican News
Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
While hailing the glorious role the senior combatants played
during the national liberation, Chissano urged the senior fighters
to contribute their bit in safeguarding national unity, and
promoting economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
Senior fighters in the country cover those who joined the
Mozambican Liberation Front during June 25, 1962 when the front
was formed, and September 7, 1974 when the country won indepence.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is designed to discuss ways to rejuvenate the
association of the Combatants for the National Liberation of
Mozambique on the occasion of the 10th anniversary of the
organization.
</P>
<P>
 South African President Nelson Mandela, Zimbabwean President
Robert Mugabe, former Zambian President Keneth Kaunda and other
important figures are invited to deliver speeches at the
conference, Chissano announced.
</P>
<P>
About 600 people are attending the conference which will end
Friday. 
</P>
