<HEADLINE> Kenyan Tea Prices Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Tea prices in Kenya went up at
 the export auction in the Indian Ocean port of Mombasa Monday
due to worries that the current drought may seriously damage
the 1999 crop.
</P>
<P>
The Mombasa-based Traders Africa Tea Brokers (ATB) said in a
news release available here that the tea market improved at the
weekly auction where main grades with brighter Best Pekoes 1s
(BP1s) and Pekoe Fannings 1s (PF1s), gaining five to 20 U.S.
cents while secondary grades rose by as much as five cents.
</P>
<P>
"Buyers are speculating that crop figures might drop because of
the current dry spells,'' said the ATB.
</P>
<P>
Tea yield in Kenya was expected to reach a new high of some 290
million kg last year but the dry weather in the just-ended short
rains season has cast a deep shadow over the 1999 harvest.
</P>
<P>
"What we need are sustained showers (to improve the tea
production),'' said Richard Surrey of the trade group Tea
Brokers Association of East Africa.
</P>
<P>
At the Monday day auction, Best BP1s traded at 2.37-2.44
Dollars per kg while PF1s were posted at 2.25-2.35 Dollars per kg
compared to 2.32-2.50 Dollars per kg and 2.10-2.21 Dollars per kg
respectively last week.
</P>
<P>
ATB said Egypt and Pakistan continued to lend strong support
while Britain bought selectively in line with quality.
</P>
</TEXT>
