<HEADLINE> Arab League Regrets Iraq's Statement on Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Arab League Secretary General
Esmat Abdel-Meguid expressed surprise Monday at the latest
statements made by Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz
concerning Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Abdel-Meguid regretted that Aziz made
the statement, which he said would "likely (have) negative impact
on" the upcoming Arab foreign ministers meeting.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's Al Thawrah newspaper, the mouthpiece of the ruling Baath
party, on Sunday quoted Aziz as claiming that Kuwait is "part of
Iraq since ancient time." This showed an about-face on Iraq's 1994
recognition of the current Iraqi-Kuwaiti border.
</P>
<P>
"It is our hope that such statements would not have been made
at this particular time," Abdel-Meguid said.
</P>
<P>
The chief of the Cairo-based Arab organization criticized
Aziz's statement as being "not conducive to creating the
atmosphere needed to boost understanding."
</P>
<P>
Arab countries originally decided to hold a foreign ministers'
meeting last month to discuss a Yemeni call for an Arab summit on
the latest developments of the Iraqi issue after the military
attack on Iraq by the United States and Britain in mid-December.
</P>
<P>
At the request of Kuwait, Saudi Arabia and other Gulf
countries, the meeting was put off until January 24. 
</P>
</TEXT>
