<HEADLINE> Rebel-Held Kisangani in DRC Bombed, Witness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Troops backing Congo (K)'s
President Laurent Kabila have air-raided the rebel-held Kisangani
in the eastern Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), claiming some
40 lives, a media report quoted aid workers in the country as
saying Monday.
</P>
<P>
The bombing reportedly broke out Sunday night, leading to the
general close-down of markets and shops Monday in the third
largest city in the DRC, said aid workers.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the allied forces from Zimbabwe, Angola, Chad
and Namibia shoring up Kabila's army confirmed the bombing in
capital Kinshasa Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, he has given no details.
</P>
<P>
"It's true Kisangani was bombed last night,'' he was quoted by
the report reaching here as saying. Kisangani is the most
important town held by rebels since the civil war in DRC erupted
in August, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The aid workers, quoting their contacts in the jungle city,
said that the bombs fell close to a former residence of
guerrilla commander Jean- Pierre Ondekane who had reportedly moved
out of the house two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the DRC government also announced that loyalist
forces had retaken two rebel-held towns in the north.
</P>
<P>
"The FAC (Congolese army) and allies have just liberated Gemena
and Libenge,'' a statement broadcast on state radio said.
</P>
<P>
According to the governmental statement, 117 rebel fighters
were killed during the offensive on Gemena, including many
Rwandans and Ugandans. 
</P>
