<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Troops Recapture State House in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, January 11 (Xinhua) -- The West African peace-keeping
force ECOMOG has successfully taken control of the State House in
Sierra Leone capital of Freetown.
</P>
<P>
The statement issued by the Economic Community of West African
States (ECOWAS) headquarters in Nigerian capital Abuja Monday said
that its peace- keeping troops had driven rebels from the State
House near the center of the capital city.
</P>
<P>
"The rebels are now being pushed out of Freetown following
reinforcement by ECOMOG" during the past several days, it said,
adding that "efforts are being made to flush the rebels out of
private residences in Freetown where some of them are still taking
refuge."
</P>
<P>
In an interview through telephone, ECOWAS Secretary-General
Lansana Kouyate said in Abuja that "as I speak to you now, I can
confirm the State House is under ECOMOG control."
</P>
<P>
He said that the rebels were now in disarray with some of them
fleeing into the bush and others hiding among the civilian
population.
</P>
<P>
However, the secretary-general pointed out that ECOWAS remained
 committed to its two pronged approaches of diplomacy and military
action to resolve the Sierra Leonean crisis.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that the foreign ministers of Togo, current ECOWAS
chairman, and Cote d'Ivoire were already in Sierra Leone to follow
up on the negotiations begun last week by President Ahmad Tejan
Kabbah and the jailed leader of the Revolutionary United Front
(RUF) Foday Sankoh.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, Kouyate will travel to Lome Tuesday
to meet Togolese President Gnassingbe Eyadema, current ECOWAS
Chairman, for emergency talks on the situation in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
It noted that "consultations are currently going on between
ECOWAS heads of state and parties to the conflict with a view to
convening a dialogue meeting as soon as possible on the crisis".
</P>
<P>
During the past two days, several hundreds of Nigerian soldiers
have been sent to Sierra Leone to reinforce the 15,000 ECOMOG
troops which have been battling for the control of the capital
city with the rebels since last Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
