<HEADLINE> U.S. Plans to Send More F-16 to Southern No-Fly Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 11 (Xinhua) -- The United States plans to
send eight more F-16 warplanes to further enforce the southern
no-fly zone in Iraq, a U.S. defense spokesman said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The eight additional jet fighters, which are specially adapted
to carry sophisticated missiles to destroy anti-aircraft radars,
would also be joined by four more aerial refueling tankers, said
Major Joe LaMarca, a spokesman for U.S. Central Command in
Tampa, Florida.
</P>
<P>
The additional F-16 warplanes would bring the total number of
U.S. aircraft patrolling the southern zone to 193.
</P>
<P>
The air reinforcements coincide with an increase in tension
between Iraq and U.S.-British forces patrolling the Iraqi northern
and southern no-fly zones, imposed after the Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Monday, two incidents happened over the northern
no-fly zone when U.S. patrolling planes fired missiles at two
Iraqi air defense sites after determining they were about to be
attacked by surface-to-air missiles.
</P>
<P>
In the one case, two U.S. F-15E strike aircraft on routing
patrol were illuminated by radar from an Iraqi surface-to-air
missile installation, and the U.S. strike aircraft fired two
AGM-130 air-to-surface missiles in response.
</P>
<P>
In the other case, an American F-16 fired one anti-radar
missile after being targeted by Iraqi radar at a separate air
defense installation near Mosul.
</P>
<P>
"The illumination of an aircraft is certainly a hostile act,
requiring the U.S. pilots to response," a Pentagon spokesman
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
