<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Butler Says UNSCOM Not Dead and He Will Not Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Chief U.N. weapons inspector
Richard Butler said Monday that U.N. weapons inspections would not
be dead and he would not resign.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a conference on arms non-proliferation, Butler
said, "UNSCOM (U.N. Special Commission) was not dead." He
predicted there might be a compromise in the U.N. Security Council
of future inspection operations in Iraq, which were halted after
four-day bombing raids against Iraqi targets by U.S. and British
missiles.
</P>
<P>
He expressed confidence that the Security Council would
maintain the organization although some changes might be required.
</P>
<P>
"I think the international community remains determined to
preserve the non-proliferation objectives (of the UNSCOM) and get
the job done with Iraq," he said.
</P>
<P>
Asked after the conference, sponsored by the Carnegie Endowment
for International Peace if he would resign, Butler replied,
"Absolutely not."
</P>
<P>
Pressure has mounted on Butler to resign after allegations were
published last week that the UNSCOM acted as spies for the United
States. Russia has urged him to quit and France called for a new
weapons monitoring organization.
</P>
<P>
Butler repeated his denial that the UNSCOM had been used as a
spy instrument, saying: "UNSCOM has not been used as a spy
organization." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990112.0360 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British PM Says Britain, France Discuss Way Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 11 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
said on Monday that Britain is discussing with France and other
U.N. Security Council members ways for going out of the Iraqi
crisis other than military strikes.
</P>
<P>
In an article contributed to the French left-leaning daily
Liberation, Blair said that Britain and the United States were not
seeking to play the role of world policeman by staging the "Desert
Fox" operation, but because it was right to do so.
</P>
<P>
"We are holding talks with France and other members of the
(U.N.) Security Council to find a formula allowing checks and
monitoring to resume in Iraq, but under a system that would avoid
the inspectors' presence creating crises from time to time," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Britain would make proposals on improving the
situation of humanitarian supply to Iraq through the "Oil for
Food" program and on increasing medicine supply to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
While saying that Britain and the United States will stage new
strikes if Iraq continues to attack British and American warplanes
above the no-fly zones, he said that one should not be stuck in
the "vicious circle of military strikes."
</P>
<P>
"Iraq can very well choose another way out," he said, adding
that once U.N. arms inspectors return to Iraq, the Iraqi
government should show "good will" by allowing them to look for
the missing chemical and biological arms.
</P>
<P>
Blair also said that those who think that Saddam Hussein would
cooperate better if sanctions were lifted are "covering their own
eyes."
</P>
<P>
France has proposed lifting the oil embargo on Iraq while
maintaining a new surveillance mechanism in Iraq to make sure that
Iraq would not become militarily dangerous again.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine discussed the proposal
with his British counterpart Robin Cook last Friday in Paris, and
he will discuss it with his Russian and Chinese counterparts this
week, according to diplomatic sources.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
